WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:16.920
First of all, let me say thank you from SNAD for the scientific help on Apollo 16.

00:16.920 --> 00:22.240
I personally think that you all did a very credible job in helping the science support

00:22.240 --> 00:29.200
room and preflighting to get all the experiments ready to prepare the crew and the flight for

00:29.200 --> 00:31.320
Apollo 16.

00:31.320 --> 00:36.640
I think that looking back on it now we can say we had a very successful mission, that we

00:36.640 --> 00:39.460
obtained a tremendous amount of information from the flight.

00:39.460 --> 00:44.580
I know that the rock boxes back there at the curatorial facility are bursting at their

00:44.580 --> 00:48.460
seams and the geologists are going to have a lot to do.

00:48.460 --> 00:54.380
I think also that because of the problems that arose and the necessity to change the

00:54.380 --> 00:58.600
flight plan that you responded quite well to get the maximum science out of the time that

00:58.600 --> 01:00.720
we had available.

01:00.720 --> 01:06.020
I realize that in all of our flights there hasn't been one flight yet that ran according

01:06.020 --> 01:13.120
to schedule and I am very sure that Apollo 17 will be in the same boat, that we will have

01:13.120 --> 01:18.900
to change things real time to get the maximum science out of the mission.

01:18.900 --> 01:22.020
And I think the response on this flight was superb.

01:22.020 --> 01:29.460
Now today the briefing here is in two parts and for two purposes.

01:29.460 --> 01:37.020
First of all I like each principal investigator to briefly describe the results so far obtained

01:37.020 --> 01:39.600
from his work.

01:39.600 --> 01:45.800
This is to sort of educate the crew on what we obtained so far from Apollo 16 so that they

01:45.800 --> 01:49.080
might have information along that line.

01:49.080 --> 01:52.820
Also I like to have him describe any anomalies that might have occurred that we do not know

01:52.820 --> 01:54.880
about now.

01:54.880 --> 02:02.560
And second, then we like to have the PI with the crew working with them to answer, have the

02:02.560 --> 02:08.920
crew answer any questions that might still be puzzling him so that he might further his analysis

02:08.920 --> 02:10.600
of the data.

02:10.600 --> 02:15.320
We have a lot of people to go through today, a lot of science to cover, so we like to keep

02:15.320 --> 02:19.840
each briefing short and we don't want to cover things that are pretty well, that are general

02:19.840 --> 02:24.740
knowledge as of today.

02:24.740 --> 02:28.820
And we can start right out.

02:28.820 --> 02:35.740
First one is Palmer Dial, Lunar Service Magnetometer.

02:35.740 --> 02:42.140
After each experimenter describes his experiment we'll have questions Palmer so we'll, we can

02:42.140 --> 02:47.740
ask the crew any questions after your particular talk.

02:47.740 --> 03:03.140
There's a mic, mic right over there.

03:03.140 --> 03:06.420
You may sit, stand, anything you want to do.

03:06.420 --> 03:15.900
The, I guess the main functions of both instruments went nominally.

03:15.900 --> 03:23.220
The, I'd like to cover both the portable and the surface, if that's acceptable.

03:23.220 --> 03:30.760
The, the, the ALSEP instrument, the surface magnetometer that you deployed first looked like

03:30.760 --> 03:35.140
it went according to plan.

03:35.140 --> 03:39.640
The field that we measured as soon as it was turned on, I think it was turned on about 15

03:39.640 --> 03:49.140
minutes or so after you deployed it, was 230 gamma and in a downward direction.

03:49.140 --> 03:55.260
And at that particular time that was the highest field that we'd ever measured on the, on the

03:55.260 --> 03:59.900
lunar surface.

03:59.900 --> 04:05.140
The calibration of the instrument went straight forward.

04:05.140 --> 04:10.240
We did do a gradient determination of the field at the site that, the site survey as we

04:10.240 --> 04:19.520
call it, uh, function normally, the, um, it's, uh, thermal control subsystem is the best that

04:19.520 --> 04:21.120
we've put on the moon so far.

04:21.120 --> 04:29.400
We have a delta T from a lunar day to lunar night of, uh, 51 degrees centigrade, which is

04:29.400 --> 04:35.540
a factor of two better than our Apollo 12 thermal subsystem.

04:35.540 --> 04:43.420
The, uh, leveling of the device was, uh, I noticed in the photograph yesterday that, uh, the bubble

04:43.420 --> 04:48.060
level was right in the center ring, the, uh, level sensors that we have are accurate to

04:48.060 --> 04:55.860
a quarter of a degree and they show that, uh, uh, that the instrument, um, is level to one

04:55.860 --> 04:58.860
degree accuracy right now.

04:58.860 --> 05:06.980
The, um, um, um, the instrument has new sensors in it.

05:06.980 --> 05:12.060
These are more stable and, uh, it's really the first chance we have of doing network type

05:12.060 --> 05:14.440
measurements of the fields on the moon.

05:14.440 --> 05:20.240
We do see whole moon, we have seen simultaneous data now from 15 and 16.

05:20.240 --> 05:28.120
We see the magnetic fields due to eddy currents that are driven in the entire lunar sphere.

05:28.120 --> 05:32.540
And, uh, for the first time experimentally, we have always made that assumption that we've

05:32.540 --> 05:36.260
got an instrument that's setting on a, at one point on a sphere and that we're looking

05:36.260 --> 05:39.280
at the properties of a whole sphere.

05:39.280 --> 05:41.940
And we had some experimental evidence that that was the case.

05:41.940 --> 05:47.780
Now we have unambiguously shown with this second instrument that that is indeed the case

05:47.780 --> 05:52.540
and that the assumption is correct that we are looking at a whole spherical response

05:52.540 --> 05:53.540
of the moon.

05:53.540 --> 05:54.540
The, um.

05:54.540 --> 05:57.160
You mean you're seeing eddy currents all the way through the moon, huh?

05:57.160 --> 06:02.120
We're seeing eddy currents that go travel around the whole sphere, but, uh, with these

06:02.120 --> 06:07.480
new sensors now and with long-term data, what we, what we're going to try and do is look,

06:07.480 --> 06:11.160
as you say, right at the center of the moon as they go all the way through.

06:11.160 --> 06:15.980
Now that's, uh, what we're waiting for during the lunar night is a nice step function and

06:15.980 --> 06:21.860
a long-term, uh, both before and after so we can see, uh, this, these currents diffuse

06:21.860 --> 06:24.320
right through the center of the moon.

06:24.320 --> 06:28.860
The, um.

06:28.860 --> 06:34.680
The other thing that I think that is, uh, unique about this instrument that, that now

06:34.680 --> 06:38.820
we have a chance to look at the, uh, as mutual variations in conductivity.

06:38.820 --> 06:44.740
We can not only look at radial, uh, dependence of the electrical conductivity and calculate a temperature,

06:44.740 --> 06:50.620
but now we can look at the, uh, uh, azimuthal or angular variations between, uh, Apollo 15

06:50.620 --> 06:53.120
and Apollo 16 side.

06:53.120 --> 06:57.240
And those, and that spread is far enough so that we ought to be able to extrapolate those

06:57.240 --> 07:02.380
measurements to a great circle around the whole moon as far as azimuthal dependence.

07:02.380 --> 07:05.080
The, uh, portable magnetometer was really exciting.

07:05.080 --> 07:12.960
Um, first of all, uh, the, uh, field that, uh, the first field I think you measured was 180

07:12.960 --> 07:19.040
gamma down and in the Cayley it looked like that all the fields were, uh, in essence pointed

07:19.040 --> 07:25.960
in a downward direction and, um, uh, at the ALSEP side it was 230 gamma, up near Spook it was

07:25.960 --> 07:33.520
180 gamma and then on the other side of the LEM where you parked the rover at, um, um, at

07:33.520 --> 07:40.900
the last, uh, station it was 120 gamma and at that station you put a, um, a rock on it

07:40.900 --> 07:44.220
and it looks like we measured about 4.7 gamma from that rock.

07:44.220 --> 07:47.640
So the rock was large enough and it hasn't large enough moment that it looks like we did

07:47.640 --> 07:49.400
see a difference.

07:49.400 --> 07:55.940
These measurements do have an air bar on them that is like plus or minus, uh, uh, as much

07:55.940 --> 08:02.360
now as, uh, 5 to 10 gamma because the solar wind and all the other inductive fields that

08:02.360 --> 08:07.840
are around that have to be subtracted out of the measurements from our, uh, magnetic, uh,

08:07.840 --> 08:10.840
from the tape and data reduction.

08:10.840 --> 08:22.600
The, um, the measurements at, uh, at, um, station five, uh, were, uh, pointed upward, uh, that

08:22.600 --> 08:31.680
was a, and, uh, the measurements up near North, uh, Ray crater were pointed downward at 318 gamma.

08:31.680 --> 08:40.820
I think that there we, they, there are some, uh, things that we would, uh, we could probably

08:40.820 --> 08:47.440
say, uh, uh, making a lot of assumptions, but it looks like if this highland material is

08:47.440 --> 08:52.580
older than the other, it looks like that we have a, at least a chance of looking at the

08:52.580 --> 08:57.180
paleomagnetic history of the, of the lunar crust from these measurements.

08:57.180 --> 09:03.500
The high fields indicate that, uh, that either the, uh, the perming source, the source of

09:03.500 --> 09:09.680
this field was, um, uh, if it remains stable over the time period that the Maria was, uh,

09:09.680 --> 09:14.480
were cooling, then the, uh, highland material would indicate this high field would indicate

09:14.480 --> 09:22.180
that it, it, uh, that it indeed had a time variation in its magnitude or that the Maria,

09:22.180 --> 09:29.540
the, the flooding of the Maria basins or whatever caused the, uh, Maria basins to be as they are

09:29.540 --> 09:34.540
today, uh, demagnetized the material that, that had been there originally.

09:36.280 --> 09:40.600
It's, in other words, the Maria material is less magnetic, it seems, than this material.

09:41.340 --> 09:48.520
The, um, interesting thing too is that the, uh, that the samples, as you know, are from the,

09:48.520 --> 09:52.760
uh, the regolith and they've really physically been modified over the years.

09:52.760 --> 09:57.100
And I think that the measurements that we've obtained over, uh, over scale size in the order

09:57.100 --> 10:02.760
of 10 kilometers indicate that we're looking at a depth below, well below the regolith and

10:02.760 --> 10:11.640
that, that this is indicative of, uh, of fields that were at the moon during a, at a time period,

10:11.640 --> 10:19.460
uh, uh, before in the order of three to four billion years ago, the, uh, direction and the,

10:19.460 --> 10:26.640
the other thing that we can say now from the, um, from measurements of the solar wind, simultaneous

10:26.640 --> 10:32.520
measurements of solar wind and magnetic fields at the Apollo 12 and 15 site, we can say that

10:32.520 --> 10:40.460
these high fields that you measured at the Apollo 16 site modifies drastically the, uh, the direction

10:40.460 --> 10:44.760
and, uh, interaction of the solar wind with the moon at these places.

10:44.760 --> 10:52.520
It should, uh, channel and charge particles and, uh, either, uh, uh, at different locations,

10:52.520 --> 10:56.340
uh, asymmetrically on the lunar surface in these areas.

10:56.540 --> 11:03.360
And in some cases that one could now, uh, state that, uh, the scale size of the field are large

11:03.360 --> 11:08.840
enough so that you could form a, uh, shock and actually stand off the solar wind over small

11:08.840 --> 11:09.760
regions of the moon.

11:10.460 --> 11:15.040
Um, yes, that's covers both of them.

11:15.040 --> 11:21.260
Do you have any questions you want to ask the crew concerning, uh, anything about the deployment

11:21.260 --> 11:22.680
or any of the experiment that you didn't know about?

11:22.680 --> 11:28.500
Um, Palmer, let me ask you, what is the effect of that rock out there by the big LSM?

11:28.500 --> 11:29.500
Did that hurt it much?

11:29.500 --> 11:34.560
No, first, uh, where you, where you parked the rover the first time in the TV camera, we

11:34.560 --> 11:39.200
were, uh, extremely disturbed because the angle was such, it looked like that rock was as big

11:39.200 --> 11:40.780
as the electronics box.

11:40.780 --> 11:45.360
And it looks like that the PRAs were, were, uh, oriented.

11:45.360 --> 11:49.940
Shining right into them and all the IR radiation would really heat us up during the daytime.

11:49.940 --> 11:55.520
Uh, but then the other view, uh, showed that the rock was relatively small compared to the

11:55.520 --> 12:00.520
dimensions of the box and, uh, didn't affect the, uh, thermal, uh, subsystem at all.

12:00.520 --> 12:06.560
And magnetically, it didn't, uh, they really don't, uh, contain that much oriented field

12:06.560 --> 12:07.260
to do anything.

12:07.260 --> 12:13.920
I guess, uh, one of the things I'd like to say is this, what we intended to do was we

12:13.920 --> 12:18.040
intended to drive a hundred yards away from the, out in front of the lunar module with

12:18.040 --> 12:24.220
the, uh, with a rover and, and do a sort of a north-south traverse looking for the best

12:24.220 --> 12:27.300
place to deploy ALSEP to, to get it away from all these things.

12:27.300 --> 12:35.780
Uh, the, we ran into problems with it, with the UV, uh, and that it took longer to do that

12:35.780 --> 12:41.480
last, uh, measurements than anticipated and we couldn't do that.

12:41.480 --> 12:46.620
Uh, and I'm sure that somebody looking at the photos can find a better place out in front

12:46.620 --> 12:49.900
of the lunar module to put the total package.

12:49.900 --> 12:56.000
But I like to say that package is so big and that surface was so blocky and so full

12:56.000 --> 13:00.820
of craters that under the circumstances, I almost believe we had to take what we got.

13:00.820 --> 13:06.660
I hate to say that, but, man, I just wouldn't believe that that surface was as rough and

13:06.660 --> 13:08.760
covered with blocks as it turned out to be.

13:09.520 --> 13:13.380
I think I could have still been walking up there with that package if I'd have been looking

13:13.380 --> 13:14.840
for a, uh, level spot.

13:14.940 --> 13:18.880
I got up on top of the ridge and I looked over and said, well, there's a good place over

13:18.880 --> 13:21.900
there and I ran over there and it didn't look any better than the place I'd just been.

13:21.900 --> 13:25.120
And I, well, there's a good place over there and I ran over there and finally after about

13:25.120 --> 13:30.220
the third time I said, well, look, I'm just going to put this thing down here at best we

13:30.220 --> 13:30.520
got.

13:31.240 --> 13:35.780
But it's really blocky and a lot of fresh craters there, secondary.

13:36.520 --> 13:42.360
Well, but I, but I think that the, uh, if, uh, if you look at the, at least the magnetometers,

13:42.540 --> 13:46.320
if I looked at each of the photos that I could find where you'd taken a picture of both

13:46.320 --> 13:52.540
the, uh, LSEP magnetometer and the portable, uh, you picked, uh, you didn't put the thing

13:52.540 --> 13:57.180
next to rocks or craters on the scale size that was big enough to affect the instrument.

13:57.180 --> 14:01.020
I, I think that's the main criteria, which was, uh, observed during that.

14:01.800 --> 14:07.120
John, did you know the rationale for doing that unplanned, uh, portable magnetometer reading?

14:08.340 --> 14:09.880
No, but it doesn't make any difference.

14:10.140 --> 14:10.840
I mean, we did it.

14:10.840 --> 14:13.520
You can't explain it in real time.

14:13.660 --> 14:14.120
That's all right.

14:15.320 --> 14:22.280
Uh, one, uh, on the hardware, uh, the sun shield on the, uh, LSM, the latch didn't come

14:22.280 --> 14:28.500
loose and I kept pulling the, the arms up to try to get that latch loose.

14:28.500 --> 14:35.040
And I finally had to hold the arm down and, and, uh, get the latch, uh, loose with the

14:35.040 --> 14:35.620
other hand.

14:35.620 --> 14:38.860
And then, and then as I tried to lock the thing, the latch didn't fall off.

14:38.960 --> 14:43.040
It, it tangled up into that little wire that locks into the little ball.

14:43.260 --> 14:43.540
Yes.

14:43.940 --> 14:49.140
And, uh, that was, uh, uh, I almost left it, uh, like that without locking it.

14:49.280 --> 14:52.280
And I mean, in fact, Houston said, go ahead, uh, and leave it.

14:52.340 --> 14:56.120
But, uh, one more little effort, the thing finally dropped off.

14:56.220 --> 14:58.760
And I thought I was going to disturb the level.

14:58.760 --> 15:01.360
But if you're, it seems like you're satisfied with the level of those.

15:01.620 --> 15:01.820
Yeah.

15:01.900 --> 15:06.100
The, uh, the only thing I worry about there is that we've got a level sensor in the thing.

15:06.180 --> 15:08.500
And if you disturb that, you can sort of see that jiggle.

15:08.500 --> 15:13.260
But the, uh, the azimuth, you know, when you read that shadow graph off, that's the only

15:13.260 --> 15:15.120
measurement we get in azimuth ever.

15:15.580 --> 15:15.780
Yeah.

15:15.980 --> 15:20.620
And, uh, so as long as you could, you didn't disturb the, uh, twisting of it, then, uh, it's

15:20.620 --> 15:20.940
fine.

15:23.420 --> 15:23.820
Okay.

15:23.820 --> 15:24.280
Thank you, Palmer.

15:24.280 --> 15:30.160
Next experimenter will be, uh, Dr. Gary Latham.

15:30.500 --> 15:31.760
Passes the size of the experiment.

15:50.240 --> 15:50.640
Yes.

15:50.760 --> 15:51.420
Yes, go ahead.

15:51.420 --> 15:55.380
Question, I was talking about what, what do you wish on the field radians from there?

15:55.380 --> 15:56.380
Do you want to talk about that?

15:57.260 --> 15:59.060
Um, gradians from which institute?

15:59.060 --> 15:59.640
Oh, yeah.

15:59.640 --> 16:03.980
Oh, we don't have the, uh, you know, we've got to take out the fluctuations and so we're

16:03.980 --> 16:05.980
in from the other institute using the policy team.

16:05.980 --> 16:09.360
No, we don't have that, uh, to take some of that.

16:09.360 --> 16:09.780
Yeah.

16:09.780 --> 16:10.720
Sorry, Matt.

16:12.640 --> 16:17.160
The actual photo you took of the LSI was taken out after you had deployed the substitute,

16:17.160 --> 16:17.380
right?

16:17.380 --> 16:20.340
I, uh, the three-footer, I think, was, that's correct, yes.

16:20.340 --> 16:22.220
Well, there wasn't any disturbance.

16:22.220 --> 16:23.760
And we didn't touch it after that.

16:23.760 --> 16:24.260
Right.

16:26.300 --> 16:30.220
If there are any questions before or any time after the discussion, feel free to just raise

16:30.220 --> 16:31.220
your hand.

16:31.220 --> 16:33.100
Thank you, Mark.

16:33.100 --> 16:39.100
Mark, our fund began, as you know, with the S-4B impact on this mission.

16:39.100 --> 16:46.680
You also know we lost tracking on it prematurely, which, which, uh, meant that we were not able

16:46.680 --> 16:51.560
to get the coordinates and time of the impact independent of our own measurements.

16:51.560 --> 16:58.320
Nevertheless, we could locate it fairly well from the two near stations, 12 and 14, which

16:58.320 --> 17:02.440
made it a useful impact at the greater range up to station 15.

17:02.440 --> 17:07.320
And, uh, we are looking at those signals now.

17:07.320 --> 17:14.560
It, it, I think we can say that this, uh, peculiarly high velocity mantle, as we called it, that we

17:14.560 --> 17:22.820
had found in the 12 and 14 region can't be a global feature unless it is exceedingly thin,

17:22.820 --> 17:25.320
a thin slab of this high velocity stuff.

17:25.320 --> 17:30.300
Uh, the signals we got, and I must say this, that, that, that there's always the uncertainty

17:30.300 --> 17:35.260
that we really didn't see the first arrival up there because it was at 1100 kilometers.

17:35.260 --> 17:38.560
And the first signal you see is quite weak.

17:38.560 --> 17:42.840
There's always the uncertainty as to whether or not it is the first, the fastest traveling

17:42.840 --> 17:45.380
wave in the moment and not something else.

17:45.380 --> 17:53.940
But if it is, uh, then this very high velocity material that we called mantle is not global or

17:53.940 --> 17:58.420
an exceedingly thin layer, looks as though we get velocities approaching eight kilometers

17:58.420 --> 18:04.940
per second at depths of the moon of, of the order of a hundred kilometers, not nine kilometers

18:04.940 --> 18:08.900
per second as we had in the 12 and 14 region.

18:08.900 --> 18:12.520
There's also very weak evidence from that signal.

18:12.520 --> 18:17.740
And I haven't convinced my colleagues of this yet nor myself really, but, uh, the possibility

18:17.740 --> 18:28.620
of a, of a reflection from a very deep interface, perhaps a 550 kilometers deep, uh, is there.

18:28.620 --> 18:31.740
And we're looking for ways to see whether or not that can be verified.

18:31.740 --> 18:36.760
In other words, a primitive core perhaps or some other reflector at very great depth.

18:36.760 --> 18:43.740
So this impact, uh, will I think provide very, very useful data despite the loss of tracking.

18:43.740 --> 18:48.280
We would have been, of course, much better off had we been able to photograph that impact

18:48.280 --> 18:49.280
area.

18:49.280 --> 18:53.500
And I, I understand that the curtailed time in orbit precluded that.

18:53.500 --> 18:54.700
Is that right, Drew?

18:54.700 --> 19:00.980
We did not photograph it in that S-4B, yeah.

19:00.980 --> 19:02.180
The deployment was good.

19:02.180 --> 19:04.060
I think the pictures tell the story.

19:04.060 --> 19:10.460
As far as I'm concerned, the, uh, instrument does get hot during a lunar day as the other

19:10.460 --> 19:11.460
instruments have.

19:11.460 --> 19:13.300
This has been the case in every one.

19:13.300 --> 19:18.120
I think it's a matter of just, it's just not possible to keep dust off of that shroud.

19:18.120 --> 19:23.100
I think when you have to work that close to it and, uh, that that degrades the, the thermal

19:23.100 --> 19:26.640
control some, it does not degrade the seismic data.

19:26.640 --> 19:31.460
It simply means that the, uh, controllers have more work to do trying to, to maintain the thermal

19:31.460 --> 19:32.460
stability.

19:32.460 --> 19:37.080
And, uh, it's a problem we faced in every, every one of the missions.

19:37.080 --> 19:38.080
So it's not.

19:38.080 --> 19:43.960
In fact, I thought the deployment, uh, uh, the configuration of the shroud that I saw

19:43.960 --> 19:46.300
and so on, uh, look, look very, very good.

19:46.300 --> 19:50.740
There's one little place where it's raised up is where the cable comes out underneath.

19:50.740 --> 19:56.560
It's turned on its age a little bit and, uh, uh, that of course is something of a heat loss,

19:56.560 --> 19:58.560
but it's not, not serious at all.

19:58.560 --> 19:59.560
Yeah.

19:59.560 --> 20:06.880
We, we patted that rascal down because of the 15 problems, but maybe it's, uh, before

20:06.880 --> 20:13.560
a guy leaves at, uh, ALSEP site, if he's got a problem like it, maybe it, is ALSEP on 17?

20:13.560 --> 20:14.560
Probably not.

20:14.560 --> 20:15.560
It's not.

20:15.560 --> 20:16.560
ALSEP is on the seismic.

20:16.560 --> 20:17.560
Seismic.

20:17.560 --> 20:18.560
Okay.

20:18.560 --> 20:24.240
Uh, those rascally things, uh, assume some different kind of, uh, orientation than they

20:24.240 --> 20:28.140
did before, before we left, before we left, and maybe you ought to go back one more time

20:28.140 --> 20:30.900
and make sure those things are, haven't changed.

20:30.900 --> 20:39.060
Don't ask me, uh, I think maybe they outgas a little and then take up a different shape.

20:39.060 --> 20:44.440
Well, it's not only, it's not only your, your near activities.

20:44.440 --> 20:50.360
I think when we saw that, that, uh, TV picture degrade on LEM ASSEN, it's obvious that a lot

20:50.360 --> 20:55.480
of debris is being thrown around and you just can't avoid a good dusting down from that source.

20:55.480 --> 21:00.960
So our, our carefully prepared thermal surfaces act more like black bodies than anybody figured

21:00.960 --> 21:05.480
on as a result of all of this.

21:05.480 --> 21:09.820
Then we saw your rover signals, which this time, uh, provided, uh, very, very interesting

21:09.820 --> 21:16.820
data, uh, in that they showed rather abrupt changes in signal level as you moved around.

21:16.820 --> 21:22.580
Uh, we're not sure yet what to make of that.

21:22.580 --> 21:28.740
We're going to work with Bill Mulberger and his crew carefully on the traverse to see whether

21:28.740 --> 21:36.820
or not we can identify specific provinces in which the signal level is quite a bit higher.

21:36.820 --> 21:45.000
I guess I, I would like to ask your impression, uh, as you were rolling along and given, along

21:45.000 --> 21:52.640
the given EVAs that you, you felt at, at given times that the rover was bouncing, uh, noticeably

21:52.640 --> 21:58.100
more than at other times that might have generated higher signal levels.

21:58.100 --> 22:01.280
Sometimes she was off the ground.

22:01.280 --> 22:03.720
There's no doubt about that.

22:03.720 --> 22:11.820
To the, uh, south, uh, EVA 2, that area was a lot rougher than the, uh, traverse route to

22:11.820 --> 22:13.980
North Ray Crater.

22:13.980 --> 22:19.860
My impression of North Ray Crater traverse once we passed Palmetto was, it was really boulder-free

22:19.860 --> 22:20.860
area.

22:20.860 --> 22:27.860
Very subdued, old craters, and the rover just sped along, and much like, uh, West Texas-type

22:27.860 --> 22:28.860
terrain.

22:28.860 --> 22:33.860
Whereas to the south, it was, uh, really rough.

22:33.860 --> 22:34.860
John had to maneuver.

22:34.860 --> 22:38.900
And particularly on Survey Ridge, when we were traversing that area with all the secondaries

22:38.900 --> 22:46.240
and blocks, uh, we managed to be up in here quite a bit, uh, simply because there were so

22:46.240 --> 22:51.800
many secondaries and blocks that we had to hit some small ones to avoid the big ones.

22:51.800 --> 23:00.620
The, uh, subjective opinion of mine also is that around, at least at stop 13 where we

23:00.620 --> 23:08.540
actually got off the rover, uh, the regolith did not seem as, as loosely compacted as to

23:08.540 --> 23:09.540
the south.

23:09.540 --> 23:14.680
And, in fact, at North Ray Crater, at Station 11 and 12, it was no more than a couple inches

23:14.680 --> 23:19.860
deep because we couldn't get the rake in without bending the tines of the rake.

23:19.860 --> 23:24.960
So the regolith up there was very thin, uh, and I don't know whether that means there's

23:24.960 --> 23:32.620
a, just some very cobbly, uh, densely compacted blocks under there from, that were thrown out

23:32.620 --> 23:37.040
or, or that are now that much covered or whether we just picked some bad sites.

23:37.040 --> 23:41.920
But we tried to rake twice and both times the only luck we had was kicking stuff into the

23:41.920 --> 23:42.920
rake.

23:42.920 --> 23:43.920
We couldn't pull the rake through the regolith.

23:43.920 --> 23:44.920
And you couldn't stick the tongs in either.

23:44.920 --> 23:45.920
And the tongs wouldn't go in.

23:45.920 --> 23:48.920
And every other place you could take the tongs and stick into the ground, they'd stand

23:48.920 --> 23:49.920
up for you.

23:49.920 --> 23:56.920
Well, you know, in general, this area from, from the general character of our signals,

23:56.920 --> 24:03.140
it gives the appearance of being the thickest pile of, of what we can quite loosely call regolith

24:03.140 --> 24:05.140
of any of the sites.

24:05.140 --> 24:09.140
And I guess Bob Kovach will talk on his results on, on that.

24:09.140 --> 24:13.380
And, and of course we await his, his, uh, motor firing to give us a little more information

24:13.380 --> 24:14.380
on that.

24:14.380 --> 24:19.220
Well, we'll be looking at these rover signals and see if we can, we can somehow pin them

24:19.220 --> 24:24.740
down to, to roughness of terrain or, or just what, uh, from the pictures that you took

24:24.740 --> 24:27.140
along the way.

24:27.140 --> 24:33.940
Uh, we now have the, the quiet nighttime period and we're waiting for the first moonquake

24:33.940 --> 24:38.980
of this session, which, which, uh, ought to be, well, I was hoping it would be in the

24:38.980 --> 24:39.980
last 24 hours.

24:39.980 --> 24:43.300
It wasn't, uh, but should be before May 12th.

24:43.300 --> 24:48.500
So in the next few days, and, and of course with this last station, we now have completed

24:48.500 --> 24:50.700
a very nice triangular array.

24:50.700 --> 24:53.940
The other three gave us a very narrow base thing.

24:53.940 --> 25:00.060
Now we have a thing with a thousand kilometer baseline, which, which if it lasts for as long

25:00.060 --> 25:04.960
as, uh, uh, they appear to be lasting, will give us the tools to really do the job over

25:04.960 --> 25:07.700
the next couple of years.

25:07.700 --> 25:13.560
Uh, and of course we'll be using that in the S-IVB impact from the next mission.

25:13.560 --> 25:20.220
I'd like to turn to, to one observation reported from orbit that, that has interested us a great

25:20.220 --> 25:27.020
deal. And that was the flash that was reported. I, I haven't seen, I understand the transcript

25:27.020 --> 25:29.240
is now, it hasn't yet been typed.

25:29.240 --> 25:33.660
I haven't seen it yet. So I, that's my only hope for pinning down the time.

25:33.660 --> 25:41.160
If you can, if you can help us pin down the time and roughly the location, and we'll certainly

25:41.160 --> 25:45.040
look at our records and that would be a, an important piece of data if we, if we recorded

25:45.040 --> 25:50.180
that. I would like to ask, was this a colored flash or a white flash?

25:50.180 --> 25:51.180
Yes.

25:51.180 --> 25:57.520
Uh, what was your, how does it differ from the kind of thing you get with a cosmic ray impact

25:57.520 --> 25:58.520
on your brain?

25:58.520 --> 25:59.520
I didn't see any of those.

25:59.520 --> 26:00.520
He didn't see any of those.

26:00.520 --> 26:01.520
I see.

26:01.520 --> 26:02.520
Redhead.

26:02.520 --> 26:19.700
Well, we're, we're very much excited by that. As far as I know, it's the first report

26:19.700 --> 26:23.700
of a transient event of some nature that's been seen from orbit.

26:23.700 --> 26:29.800
I, I just have to wait for the, I should have written it down and it just didn't occur

26:29.800 --> 26:30.800
to me to write it down.

26:30.800 --> 26:32.800
Do we get a time on it at all, Ken?

26:32.800 --> 26:33.800
It's on the DSE.

26:33.800 --> 26:34.800
It's on the DSE.

26:34.800 --> 26:35.800
If I ever get that off.

26:35.800 --> 26:40.800
Well then it would correlate any information we get to the seismic interfaces.

26:40.800 --> 26:47.800
You know, how about its persistence? Did it just, no, it was just, it was just a flash.

26:47.800 --> 26:53.400
And, and the way I happened to notice it, I was looking at a, at a horizon that was showing

26:53.400 --> 26:58.680
up from solar corona or zodiacal light, whatever you want to call it in that region.

26:58.680 --> 27:07.800
It was very shortly after we lost the signal from earth and I was watching stars pop up

27:07.800 --> 27:18.680
over the horizon and got this flash which was in size was about, I didn't, I didn't, I wasn't

27:18.680 --> 27:24.800
looking directly at it at the time, it hadn't been happening down in the side of my vision,

27:24.800 --> 27:28.800
but it was brighter than the, than the brightest star that I had in the field of view at the

27:28.800 --> 27:29.800
time.

27:29.800 --> 27:37.800
And I had the feeling that it was a, in physical or angular size, it was equivalent to the

27:37.800 --> 27:42.800
size of the larger stars in, in my perceived vision.

27:42.800 --> 27:49.800
But it was just a, it was just an instantaneous flash and that it took us a couple of seconds

27:49.800 --> 27:53.800
for it to soak into me that it wasn't just a star popping up over the horizon, but rather,

27:53.800 --> 27:58.800
it had been distinctly below the horizon.

27:58.800 --> 28:01.800
Is there a way for me to get that transcript?

28:01.800 --> 28:04.800
I don't know if I would normally get it.

28:04.800 --> 28:06.800
I'm glad, I'm glad you asked.

28:06.800 --> 28:07.800
Oh, that's it?

28:07.800 --> 28:11.800
And I forgot to mention this in the opening remarks, but we have about 50 copies of this

28:11.800 --> 28:17.800
technical air to ground voice transcript right back there and for the PIs and the COIs

28:17.800 --> 28:20.800
and there's a copy for you, Gary Beck.

28:20.800 --> 28:21.800
Gary, that's not what you're after.

28:21.800 --> 28:22.800
It won't be on now.

28:22.800 --> 28:23.800
I need the tape recorder.

28:23.800 --> 28:24.800
It won't be on now.

28:24.800 --> 28:25.800
Yeah.

28:25.800 --> 28:26.800
Oh, the DSE.

28:26.800 --> 28:27.800
It's on the DSE.

28:27.800 --> 28:28.800
And that hasn't been completed as far as I know.

28:28.800 --> 28:29.800
Okay.

28:29.800 --> 28:36.800
One other thing that I'd like to mention, from orbit it appeared to me that there was a distinctly

28:36.800 --> 28:43.800
different unit up around North Ray in an area that probably, I'd say, a third or a half

28:43.800 --> 28:46.800
of the traverse to North Ray went across.

28:46.800 --> 28:51.800
And that may or may not fit in with your seismic deltas.

28:51.800 --> 28:57.800
That at some point between North Ray and LM, they would cross a contact of some kind.

28:57.800 --> 28:58.800
Yes, sir.

28:58.800 --> 29:06.800
Well, except to add my thanks for a very fine deployment, that's all I have.

29:06.800 --> 29:07.800
Thank you.

29:07.800 --> 29:08.800
Any questions from the floor?

29:08.800 --> 29:21.800
Well, I don't know where the S4B hit, but this is on the backside of the limb, so I would

29:21.800 --> 29:23.800
assume that the S4B didn't hit there.

29:23.800 --> 29:33.800
And it was well after that, like a couple of days, lunar days.

29:33.800 --> 29:36.800
Where did the S4B impact?

29:36.800 --> 29:44.800
Oh, it hit about 150 kilometers north of Station 12.

29:44.800 --> 29:45.800
No.

29:45.800 --> 29:59.800
The time I was doing this, I was looking out the window, and I had darkened the cockpit

29:59.800 --> 30:04.800
in preparation for one of the low light level photographic exercises.

30:04.800 --> 30:08.800
And that's how I happened to be noticing that there was this distinct horizon which surprised

30:08.800 --> 30:09.800
me.

30:09.800 --> 30:12.800
And I just happened to be kind of puzzling over that at the time.

30:12.800 --> 30:13.800
Okay.

30:13.800 --> 30:14.800
Any other questions?

30:14.800 --> 30:15.800
No.

30:15.800 --> 30:16.800
Not when your visor's down.

30:16.800 --> 30:17.800
Your visor's up?

30:17.800 --> 30:18.800
I never looked with the visor.

30:18.800 --> 30:19.800
Supposed to do that.

30:19.800 --> 30:36.800
I suspect, from what we saw on EVA on the way home, that the inner visor alone has sufficient

30:36.800 --> 30:39.800
attenuation to block out the stars.

30:39.800 --> 30:43.800
But you could see them through the AOT in the lunar module.

30:43.800 --> 30:46.800
And, of course, that has a light shield around it.

30:46.800 --> 30:53.800
On our last alignment, even with a crescent Earth in the AOT, we could see Arknar.

30:53.800 --> 31:00.800
It was really so good that we didn't even have to roll up the window shades in the cockpit.

31:00.800 --> 31:07.800
So, with a proper, if you look through a tube, I'm sure you could see every star up there?

31:07.800 --> 31:12.800
The only thing we saw on the lunar surface was the Earth.

31:12.800 --> 31:14.800
And you had to, it was directly overhead.

31:14.800 --> 31:16.800
That was the only thing I saw in the sky.

31:16.800 --> 31:24.800
John, when you were looking through the sight of the camera, did you see anything beside the camera?

31:24.800 --> 31:26.800
You see your helmet reflected.

31:26.800 --> 31:27.800
That's what you see.

31:27.800 --> 31:33.800
You have to raise your visor to get all that, so you can get rid of all those reflections.

31:33.800 --> 31:38.800
Okay, next one is active seismic experiment.

31:38.800 --> 31:39.800
Dr. Kovach?

31:39.800 --> 31:56.800
Well, we had several objectives on this experiment.

31:56.800 --> 32:03.800
I'd like to summarize these basic questions like how thick is the seismic regolith would be one question.

32:03.800 --> 32:07.800
What were the in-situ physical properties of the lunar near-surface material?

32:07.800 --> 32:12.800
And thirdly, are there any distinct seismic horizons?

32:12.800 --> 32:17.800
And how do they correlate with our estimates to geological horizons?

32:17.800 --> 32:25.800
And finally, were there any regional differences in seismic velocities, i.e. something characteristically different between the Mari and the Highlands?

32:25.800 --> 32:29.800
Well, the deployment and the execution of the thumper experiment was outstanding.

32:29.800 --> 32:34.800
I mean, the records are clearer, and the background noise was sufficiently low.

32:34.800 --> 32:39.800
I mean, we got clean first breaks completely down the geophone line.

32:39.800 --> 32:40.800
Couldn't have asked for better.

32:40.800 --> 32:41.800
I'm sorry about that first one.

32:41.800 --> 32:45.800
I was so really happy when that rascal worked that I stopped walking.

32:45.800 --> 32:48.800
I started walking to the next one.

32:48.800 --> 32:54.800
Well, the record shows that for some reason you inadvertently didn't hold it in a charged position.

32:54.800 --> 32:59.800
sufficiently long enough, and that's the reason when you did it the second time it worked.

32:59.800 --> 33:04.800
No, I thought I started walking too soon after the first one went off.

33:04.800 --> 33:08.800
The one that failed, yeah, that was pure procedure there.

33:08.800 --> 33:11.800
Well, if you walked too soon, it didn't hurt us any.

33:11.800 --> 33:13.800
Didn't bother you? Okay.

33:13.800 --> 33:19.800
The data needs yet to be corrected for topographic effects.

33:19.800 --> 33:23.800
There's some severe undulations in the topography, and we can see this in the data,

33:23.800 --> 33:28.800
but I can give you some first impressions of our results.

33:28.800 --> 33:35.800
Number one, there's certainly no variability in the first arrival velocities across the geophone array,

33:35.800 --> 33:41.800
and the apparent velocity, or the velocity, is again very close to 100 meters per second,

33:41.800 --> 33:51.800
which seems to be the magic number for the regolith at many different places now on the moon,

33:51.800 --> 33:56.800
i.e. out in the Maury and now up here and finally up in this highland site.

33:56.800 --> 34:04.800
There are no evidence of flows beneath this geophone line.

34:04.800 --> 34:11.800
I feel sufficiently confident we would have recognized that.

34:11.800 --> 34:15.800
Now, the fact that we didn't recognize any variability in the velocity,

34:15.800 --> 34:23.800
we were able to say one more thing, because we recorded the limb ascent when we turned on the geophone line,

34:23.800 --> 34:29.800
and that was positioned some 140 meters away from our first geophone.

34:29.800 --> 34:37.800
And we did get a faster apparent velocity, and it's very close to the value measure for Fra Amaro for Breccius.

34:37.800 --> 34:42.800
And so, with this type of a number now, i.e. 200 to 300 meters per second underlying this regolith,

34:42.800 --> 34:50.800
we can put a thickness bound on the regolith at this site, and it is indeed very thick, at least 40 meters.

34:50.800 --> 34:57.800
And I'll be able to refine that number a little bit when we get the mortars fired.

35:01.800 --> 35:07.800
We also did turn on the ASE geophone array and recorded, you know, your rover approaching the limb during the end of EVA 3,

35:07.800 --> 35:16.800
and we also got very interesting signals, and we hope to analyze these in an analogous way, as Gary has suggested.

35:16.800 --> 35:22.800
And that's about all I can say for the quick look of our date at this point.

35:22.800 --> 35:29.800
We do have the concern, of course, I do have the concern about the grenade box deployment, I'm sure I've asked you that.

35:29.800 --> 35:35.800
I haven't seen any of the pictures yet, so maybe it'll be self-explained, but maybe you could reassure me that it's level.

35:35.800 --> 35:37.800
It's level, I guarantee you.

35:37.800 --> 35:40.800
In fact, that was probably the only level place we had it around there.

35:41.800 --> 35:47.800
And I was really pleased to see when we got out to where we could deploy it that it would be level.

35:47.800 --> 35:53.800
It's really good. And I reported the, I don't remember what azimuth heading that we put it on.

35:53.800 --> 35:59.800
It was very close. It seemed like it was 3-3-0 as opposed to 3-3-3 that it should have been on.

35:59.800 --> 36:03.800
That's off the top of my head. We had to go back and look, but I reported it.

36:03.800 --> 36:09.800
And I found out later that you could break that pin by pulling on the leg, but I certainly didn't know that.

36:09.800 --> 36:16.800
If somebody told me that doing the training, why it had gone right over my head.

36:16.800 --> 36:21.800
But we do have three good legs in there, and I'll bet you that rascal can't get out of the ground,

36:21.800 --> 36:24.800
because the way it went in, it's sort of like pushing it into quicksand.

36:24.800 --> 36:30.800
And once it gets in there, I defy anybody to get that mortar box back out of there,

36:30.800 --> 36:34.800
because it really grabbed ahold of it.

36:34.800 --> 36:39.800
Well, again, I'd like to offer my thanks for an outstanding execution of the experiment.

36:39.800 --> 36:42.800
We couldn't ask for anything better.

36:42.800 --> 36:46.800
Thank you. It was our pleasure. Boy, it really worked good. I was really pleased.

36:46.800 --> 36:48.800
Any questions from the forest?

36:48.800 --> 36:52.800
How do you define the regular size?

36:56.800 --> 37:00.800
Well, we define the regular, I don't know how the geologist may not agree with what you define,

37:00.800 --> 37:04.800
but we define it as material which apparently covers much of the lunar surface

37:04.800 --> 37:08.800
and has this characteristic velocity of 100 meters per second.

37:08.800 --> 37:10.800
And what comes up from that?

37:10.800 --> 37:17.800
Underneath this particular size, I am something that has velocities like the fraught marble, breaches.

37:17.800 --> 37:21.800
You said something about you were sure that there was no flow material underneath this.

37:21.800 --> 37:24.800
I guess I missed the conclusion.

37:24.800 --> 37:26.800
Well, we've done enough experiments on Earth,

37:26.800 --> 37:32.800
and I say that we've been able to recognize flows because the velocities are characteristically much higher.

37:32.800 --> 37:36.800
And if you want to argue that there may be very thin flows,

37:36.800 --> 37:42.800
i.e. thinner than our sampling wavelength, which is like two to three meters, they could be there.

37:42.800 --> 37:47.800
But we certainly, on the average, didn't see any big sequence of high velocity flows.

37:47.800 --> 37:52.800
When you say high velocity, this two or three hundred that you're talking about from the essence stage,

37:52.800 --> 37:53.800
that's not high enough.

37:53.800 --> 37:55.800
That's not high enough.

37:55.800 --> 38:00.800
Yes, every small crater that we looked into with exception, probably a Buster Crater,

38:00.800 --> 38:08.800
we never saw anything that looked like anything but, I mean, it just looked like more of the same,

38:08.800 --> 38:12.800
looked like regolith.

38:12.800 --> 38:15.800
I mean, you know, we never saw anything that looked like outcropper,

38:15.800 --> 38:17.800
and we were sure looking for it.

38:17.800 --> 38:21.800
This two to three hundred meter velocity,

38:21.800 --> 38:25.800
about the limb acid, that was the stretch of material that you say is underlying the regolith.

38:25.800 --> 38:26.800
Is that right?

38:26.800 --> 38:28.800
That's my first look, yeah.

38:28.800 --> 38:29.800
First look.

38:32.800 --> 38:34.800
When do you fire the mortars?

38:34.800 --> 38:35.800
Oh, that's another good question.

38:35.800 --> 38:38.800
What's the latest word on mortar firing?

38:38.800 --> 38:40.800
Do we have any idea about when?

38:40.800 --> 38:43.800
Well, there's a meeting at one o'clock this afternoon.

38:43.800 --> 38:46.800
I'm going to request to fire it on May the 23rd.

38:48.800 --> 38:50.800
Bastille Day, is that it?

38:50.800 --> 39:01.800
And it's armed, too.

39:01.800 --> 39:06.800
Okay, our next subject is the solar wind composition.

39:06.800 --> 39:08.800
Dr. Meister?

39:08.800 --> 39:23.800
Unfortunately, there is not much to tell about the solar wind composition experiment.

39:23.800 --> 39:27.800
The foil was transferred to Switzerland at the end of last week,

39:27.800 --> 39:31.800
and we don't have any results yet, of course.

39:31.800 --> 39:35.800
The foil was deployed during the first EVA

39:35.800 --> 39:39.800
and retrieved at the end of the third EVA

39:39.800 --> 39:44.800
with a total exposure time of 45 hours and five minutes.

39:44.800 --> 39:48.800
That's some three hours longer than the record of the previous missions,

39:48.800 --> 39:52.800
which was about 52 hours on Apollo 15.

39:54.800 --> 39:58.800
The main difference between the foil of Apollo 16

39:58.800 --> 40:01.800
and the ones of the previous missions

40:01.800 --> 40:08.800
is that some pieces of platinum foil have been attached to the previous design,

40:08.800 --> 40:11.800
which was composed of a pure aluminum foil.

40:11.800 --> 40:16.800
These platinum foil pieces can be cleaned by fluoridic acid,

40:16.800 --> 40:22.800
which allows to remove all the possible lunar dust contamination.

40:22.800 --> 40:28.800
This technique has been tested in the lab on bombarded foils

40:28.800 --> 40:34.800
and showed that you can remove essentially all the lunar dust contamination

40:34.800 --> 40:45.800
without losing any measurable amount of trapped rare gas ions or atoms of solar wind origin.

40:45.800 --> 40:57.800
This technique should allow us to determine the isotopic composition of the rare gas elements of solar wind origin

40:57.800 --> 41:01.800
up to the mass of possible krypton.

41:01.800 --> 41:12.800
The first visual inspection of the foil here at MSC showed that the foil is crimpled,

41:12.800 --> 41:15.800
but essentially free of lunar dust.

41:15.800 --> 41:20.800
That's of course only a visual observation.

41:20.800 --> 41:23.800
We don't know how the foil looks like under microscope.

41:23.800 --> 41:30.800
I would like to thank the crew for the proper deployment and retrieval of the foil.

41:30.800 --> 41:34.800
We are very pleased with what the foil looks like.

41:34.800 --> 41:36.800
Thank you very much.

41:36.800 --> 41:38.800
Can't miss when it tells you where the sun is.

41:38.800 --> 41:40.800
Yeah, point this at sun.

41:40.800 --> 41:45.800
The thing didn't roll up like I thought it was going to,

41:45.800 --> 41:51.800
and I'm sorry I had to crinkle it, but it was so big that I had to squeeze it down to get it into the bag,

41:51.800 --> 41:53.800
and it ripped once too.

41:53.800 --> 41:54.800
I guess you saw that.

41:54.800 --> 41:56.800
That's only a problem of aesthetics.

41:56.800 --> 41:58.800
It doesn't hurt the scientific value.

41:58.800 --> 41:59.800
Okay, good.

41:59.800 --> 42:01.800
I didn't think it did.

42:01.800 --> 42:02.800
Don?

42:02.800 --> 42:06.800
If the local magnetic fuel is standing off of a solar windier,

42:06.800 --> 42:10.800
it's going to overlap like that.

42:10.800 --> 42:22.800
We don't know yet that we have discrimination between the lighter and heavier elements in the solar wind.

42:22.800 --> 42:31.800
We have to check that maybe that there's a dependence on the height over the lunar surface of the composition

42:31.800 --> 42:37.800
between the heavier and lighter elements, but we have to check that first and see.

42:37.800 --> 42:46.800
The lighter particles would be deflected much more than the heavier ones.

42:46.800 --> 42:50.800
Can you see those, I don't know, this is probably a stupid question,

42:50.800 --> 42:58.800
but these particles that cause the light flashes, I was seeing them on the lunar surface during the sleep periods.

42:58.800 --> 43:01.800
Do those things register on your experiment?

43:01.800 --> 43:05.800
No, they have higher energies and they go through the foil.

43:05.800 --> 43:06.800
I see.

43:06.800 --> 43:07.800
Yeah.

43:07.800 --> 43:08.800
Huh?

43:08.800 --> 43:10.800
That was your question.

43:10.800 --> 43:23.800
While we were closer to thinking bulky, could you tell any difference in the materials between the time you deployed and the time you brought back?

43:23.800 --> 43:24.800
No.

43:24.800 --> 43:28.800
No difference there.

43:28.800 --> 43:32.800
Looking at it one time out the window, I thought I saw some white streaks on it,

43:32.800 --> 43:35.800
but that might have been just the way the sun was.

43:35.800 --> 43:41.800
It might have been those platinum strips that I'd never noticed when I emplaced it.

43:41.800 --> 43:42.800
I really don't know.

43:42.800 --> 43:49.800
So it just looked like it had a couple of randomly oriented streaks on it to me from the limb window.

43:49.800 --> 43:57.800
But when we rolled it back up again, instead of rolling straight up, it rolled out in a big long thing and I had to redo it again.

43:57.800 --> 44:01.800
And when that happened, I ripped it and then had to crunch it down.

44:01.800 --> 44:09.800
We don't see any difference between the foil we sent up and the foil that came down, except of some lunar dust on it.

44:09.800 --> 44:11.800
Nothing else.

44:11.800 --> 44:13.800
Can I ask the crew a question?

44:13.800 --> 44:17.800
Do you have an idea how the foil was oriented?

44:17.800 --> 44:20.800
Was it essentially vertical to the...

44:20.800 --> 44:21.800
The foregrounds.

44:21.800 --> 44:28.800
I mean along the gravitational force lines or was it reclined or inclined?

44:28.800 --> 44:31.800
It's hard to tell it from...

44:31.800 --> 44:37.800
I think I put it in almost parallel to the gravity vector there.

44:37.800 --> 44:44.800
It's on a slope, a little slope, but if I recall, it's aligned almost vertically.

44:44.800 --> 44:45.800
Okay.

44:45.800 --> 44:47.800
Thank you very much.

44:47.800 --> 44:50.800
Thank you.

44:50.800 --> 44:55.800
The next subject will be the cosmic ray detector, Dr. Bob Fleischer.

44:55.800 --> 44:58.800
See here?

44:58.800 --> 44:59.800
Oh.

44:59.800 --> 45:00.800
Okay.

45:00.800 --> 45:05.800
He's not here.

45:05.800 --> 45:10.800
The PIs could be here this morning.

45:10.800 --> 45:15.800
They're busily at home studying the data that they got back.

45:15.800 --> 45:20.800
I have some words from them that I'll pass along as to what they think they'll be able to see.

45:20.800 --> 45:25.800
They are very excited about the possibilities they have.

45:25.800 --> 45:34.800
Early in the mission there was a solar particle event that occurred which will enhance their data very significantly, they think.

45:34.800 --> 45:43.800
They think they'll have the opportunity to see particles from the sun that on an ordinary mission they would have never had the opportunity to see.

45:43.800 --> 46:02.800
When they got the experiment back, panel one did have considerable dust on it, and this, from the best we can tell without any analysis, came from the landing itself, from the blast up from the DPS.

46:02.800 --> 46:05.800
Panel one was hot.

46:05.800 --> 46:19.800
In the, taking the panels apart, panels two and three were cooler, and panel four was of the same order of temperatures as panel two and three.

46:19.800 --> 46:34.800
The cosmic ray data itself in the plastics appears to be degraded somewhat because of the temperature, but they're very hopeful that a great part of the data will be retrievable.

46:34.800 --> 46:52.800
At the first look on panel two, Dr. Flesher says that the number of particles they see on the plastics indeed are a great deal higher than they would have nominally anticipated indicating the effects of the solar particle event.

46:52.800 --> 46:59.800
And, uh, they really haven't, uh, in detail etched the plastics or analyzed them, they're just beginning to do that.

46:59.800 --> 47:00.800
They think they are usable?

47:00.800 --> 47:01.800
Yes, the plastics.

47:01.800 --> 47:17.800
I was really surprised because, uh, we had some lengthy discussions about this pre-flight, and I could never understand how we're gonna fly this rascal to the moon and get it there with this, with these long periods of attitude hold that we're going into where it might see plus 250 all the time.

47:17.800 --> 47:29.800
And, uh, of course, I'm sure those three revs in lunar orbit prior to landing didn't do any good, uh, either, because we were oriented, uh, many times so that we were facing with, uh, to maintain communications.

47:29.800 --> 47:33.800
We had the sun shining on that rascal, uh, all the way around.

47:33.800 --> 47:45.800
And, uh, I really think it, those 140 temperatures that we saw on the panels, if you go back and look at it thermally, you're gonna find out they were there.

47:45.800 --> 47:48.800
It had to be there long before we ever got the thing on the ground.

47:48.800 --> 47:49.800
Uh.

47:49.800 --> 47:55.800
You know, and I was really concerned about that as to why we didn't put some kind of shield in over it, but it was too late, I guess, to do that sort of thing.

47:55.800 --> 48:02.800
Well, the thermal design was such that it could sit, I believe, in direct sunlight almost indefinitely without any degradation.

48:02.800 --> 48:07.800
It's the IR heating off the lunar surface that really cooks it from, that's what the thermal people say.

48:07.800 --> 48:17.800
Uh, I think, and it's hard to say, and I, we did see the, the early picture did show that the temple labels had already changed, uh, early at the beginning of the EVA.

48:17.800 --> 48:19.800
They were black first time we looked at them.

48:19.800 --> 48:20.800
Right.

48:20.800 --> 48:35.800
And, uh, uh, a guess is the 15 hours, the, the thermal analysis says if there's like 15% dust on the panel after, uh, 20, uh, degrees of sun angle or so, you will sort of exceed the 140 degrees on the frame.

48:35.800 --> 48:44.800
Uh, it appeared that there was probably 50 or 60% dust on the lower part of the panel, or maybe even higher than that, and it spent about 15 hours on the surface.

48:44.800 --> 48:54.800
Uh, so it, it may have just turned out to be a, a number of problems that, uh, probably, uh, ones that could not be avoided under the circumstances that caused that lower panel to overheat.

48:54.800 --> 49:03.800
It was the hottest, and the next panel was, uh, about 20 degrees cooler, the best we can tell, and the panel, third panel up was 10 degrees cooler than the second panel.

49:03.800 --> 49:09.800
So it seemed to be a dust problem, but, uh, it doesn't seem to, to have hurt the data too much.

49:09.800 --> 49:19.800
Panel four was the one, uh, which, uh, was, uh, we were afraid wasn't going to be activated because of the anomaly on the red lanyard.

49:19.800 --> 49:26.800
But after they have taken the panel apart, apparently every portion of the experiment was activated to some degree or another.

49:26.800 --> 49:32.800
The neutron portion, uh, was partially, uh, deployed, and they think they will get some data from it.

49:32.800 --> 49:35.800
It's not, not as much data statistically as they wish they had.

49:35.800 --> 49:42.800
But, uh, uh, every portion of panel four, uh, uh, does look like it will provide some, uh, some useful data.

49:42.800 --> 49:47.800
And they, uh, have a lot, uh, higher hopes now than they did when they first saw the gear.

49:47.800 --> 49:52.800
Apparently the problem, and we haven't, again, haven't sent the hardware back to the manufacturer for analysis,

49:52.800 --> 49:59.800
but apparently was, uh, a malfunction in the assembly, uh, that caused that, uh, thing to jam.

49:59.800 --> 50:06.800
Well, we could have pulled, if I'd have known about it at the time, uh, we could have got that pair of pliers out of there and pulled harder.

50:06.800 --> 50:09.800
The investigator's opinion was it would have done no good.

50:09.800 --> 50:15.800
It was very severely jammed, and, uh, he doesn't think any additional effort would have, would have, uh, would have freed it.

50:15.800 --> 50:17.800
It was jammed pretty bad.

50:17.800 --> 50:18.800
Okay.

50:18.800 --> 50:26.800
But, uh, I think in all, they're, they're very excited about the data, and I think they're very optimistic now that they'll get a considerable amount of data from it.

50:26.800 --> 50:32.800
Tim, it's probably worth mentioning on all the plastic panels overheated, but they did have calibration plastics in there,

50:32.800 --> 50:37.800
and they'd be able to, but the effect would be overheated just to anneal the cracks and reduce the crack density,

50:37.800 --> 50:40.800
but with the calibration in there, they'd be, they'd almost have an effect.

50:40.800 --> 50:45.800
The other thing is that on panel four is that those experiments which are activated by pulling the cord

50:45.800 --> 50:52.800
are only a small fraction of the total part of the panel cord, so there's a lot of panel four that isn't involved at all.

50:52.800 --> 50:53.800
That's true.

50:53.800 --> 50:59.800
The, uh, that's for all practical purposes.

50:59.800 --> 51:00.800
Okay.

51:00.800 --> 51:09.800
I don't think we, uh, in fact, I'm sure we, you may find a fingerprint on there, but if there is, it, we, uh,

51:09.800 --> 51:14.800
we really were careful, uh, to get it out of there, and we didn't, uh, once we got it loose,

51:14.800 --> 51:22.800
we gave the usual 10-11 care and folded it up, so I don't think there's any crew fingerprints on the panel surfaces.

51:22.800 --> 51:27.800
Uh, that's correct. We looked at it very carefully, and it was, except for the bottom part of the panel one,

51:27.800 --> 51:33.800
that you could see it was a spray pattern, and, uh, it was very clean, and the PIs were very pleased about that.

51:33.800 --> 51:34.800
Okay.

51:34.800 --> 51:39.800
This, uh, cell type of event, did you notice more than that occurred?

51:39.800 --> 51:47.800
Yes, it started on about, uh, I believe Monday, which was the day after launch, and went through about Wednesday.

51:47.800 --> 51:56.800
It was about a two- or three-day type event. I think the peak was, uh, must have been about Tuesday.

51:56.800 --> 52:04.800
There are some satellite data available, and I don't have that on hand.

52:04.800 --> 52:09.800
It was a small event, but for this solar cycle, it was very surprising that it happened at all during the mission,

52:09.800 --> 52:14.800
that to have it during the portion when the cosmic ray was deployed, or available to accept data,

52:14.800 --> 52:19.800
the probability of that's very small, so it's a very gratifying thing to occur.

52:19.800 --> 52:25.800
I'm curious about the, uh, dust being kicked up by the DPS.

52:25.800 --> 52:32.800
Um, did you guys observe any dust on the thing, or any other part of the limb at that level?

52:32.800 --> 52:37.800
Because, uh, it's always been our impression that the dust is sent out in a pretty thin layer,

52:37.800 --> 52:40.800
but you don't get a billowing effect.

52:40.800 --> 52:42.800
Yeah, I'm sure it's sent out in a thin layer,

52:42.800 --> 52:47.800
but with all those frontal blocks around there, it's a possibility some of it could come back at you, that's for sure.

52:47.800 --> 52:48.800
Yeah.

52:48.800 --> 52:53.800
It was extremely hard to see, and when we photographed it, the lights are not similar to the sun,

52:53.800 --> 52:58.800
probably much less in intensity, but yet the photographic lights did wash out.

52:58.800 --> 53:02.800
It's a very pale, uh, kind of dust, but it's very predominant.

53:02.800 --> 53:07.800
And it came up from the corner, Dave, in a pattern that you would expect it to be blown,

53:07.800 --> 53:12.800
and there were some black streaks in there that appeared to be melted something or other on it.

53:12.800 --> 53:15.800
And I think they are going to attempt to chemically analyze the material on it,

53:15.800 --> 53:16.800
and try to find out what it is.

53:16.800 --> 53:22.800
How high above the surface, or up, down the left?

53:23.800 --> 53:27.800
That first panel must be about chest high, is it not?

53:27.800 --> 53:28.800
Okay.

53:28.800 --> 53:29.800
Yeah.

53:29.800 --> 53:32.800
Any other questions?

53:32.800 --> 53:34.800
One, just one comment.

53:34.800 --> 53:37.800
That was, uh, the frame of that thing was hot, really, it was hot.

53:37.800 --> 53:41.800
That was the only thing I felt through my gloves the whole state.

53:41.800 --> 53:45.800
Well, it was jammed, and John tried to pull it out, and I was holding the frame,

53:45.800 --> 53:47.800
and I started feeling it through my gloves.

53:47.800 --> 53:51.800
Did you get any feel for why it was jamming, or where it was jamming?

53:51.800 --> 53:53.800
Did you have any clue, or what caused it?

53:53.800 --> 53:54.800
It was jamming at the base.

53:54.800 --> 53:55.800
Yeah, not at the bottom.

53:55.800 --> 53:57.800
Right, right at the bottom part.

54:00.800 --> 54:03.800
Yeah, it was something that broke free right at the base,

54:03.800 --> 54:07.800
and then it just came out like it had grease on it.

54:08.800 --> 54:10.800
Maybe we spilled some orange juice on it or something.

54:12.800 --> 54:13.800
No way.

54:13.800 --> 54:18.800
That's the only thing we didn't spill orange juice on.

54:21.800 --> 54:22.800
It's not that you didn't try, huh?

54:24.800 --> 54:26.800
That's a good cement, you guys.

54:26.800 --> 54:28.800
You ought to start thinking about that.

54:28.800 --> 54:30.800
Dispose that stuff to vacuum, boy.

54:32.800 --> 54:36.800
Okay, our next experiment was the far-UV camera.

54:36.800 --> 54:37.800
Dr. Page?

54:37.800 --> 54:47.800
Well, for the benefit of some of the geologists here, I'll recount the goals and purposes of this experiment,

54:47.800 --> 54:58.800
which were to obtain photographs in the far ultraviolet of the geocorona in the upper atmosphere of the Earth.

54:59.800 --> 55:02.800
I should have said these photographs, of course, include spectra as well.

55:02.800 --> 55:17.800
And solar wind, clouds, possibly interstellar hydrogen, colors of stars in the far ultraviolet, and possibly intergalactic hydrogen.

55:17.800 --> 55:21.800
We had a lot of troubles, I guess John well knows.

55:22.800 --> 55:34.800
Before launch, the difficulty was to keep the camera dry because its optically sensitive surface would immediately run away if it got damp.

55:34.800 --> 55:45.800
And this was accomplished with a bag that caused Captain Young a little bit of trouble in the practices in advance,

55:45.800 --> 55:47.800
but apparently worked all right on the lunar surface.

55:47.800 --> 55:48.800
That's great.

55:49.800 --> 55:54.800
The second difficulty was getting through the Van Allen belts without fogging our film,

55:54.800 --> 56:01.800
and I'll show you in a moment that we did that all right with a rather small amount of shielding around the film cassette.

56:01.800 --> 56:09.800
Then we had some difficulty with the limb being in the way.

56:09.800 --> 56:14.800
This came about because of the delay in touchdown, high sun angle,

56:14.800 --> 56:19.800
and the necessity to keep the camera close to the limb so that it would be in the shadow.

56:20.800 --> 56:26.800
With its gold surface, it would have heated up very rapidly if it had been out in the full sunlight.

56:26.800 --> 56:42.800
The accomplishments that I will show you in a moment on the screen include 92 photographs in Limon Alpha imagery,

56:42.800 --> 56:49.800
and 53 spectra, some of them extending from 500 angstroms to 1550 angstroms.

56:49.800 --> 56:56.800
That's, I think, the farthest into the ultraviolet anybody's ever taken astronomical pictures.

56:56.800 --> 57:07.800
We may get evidence of gases in the lunar atmosphere from several of our pointings which were low across the lunar horizon.

57:07.800 --> 57:17.800
And if anything were coming out like geysers of water or whatever it is, we'll certainly pick it up.

57:17.800 --> 57:26.800
The data on these photographs are extremely numerous, and it'll take us an estimated six months to a year to get them all out,

57:26.800 --> 57:30.800
which will be done with the big computer here at the MSC.

57:30.800 --> 57:35.800
So, Dr. George Carruthers, who is the PI and who designed the camera,

57:35.800 --> 57:40.800
happened to be free today from work on an Arabi flight, and he's here,

57:40.800 --> 57:45.800
and will undoubtedly make comments whenever he sees something to comment on the photographs.

57:45.800 --> 57:47.800
Do we have the first slide?

57:47.800 --> 57:52.800
I might say that I got into trouble with the American Photographers' Union in thanking the prints of these,

57:52.800 --> 57:58.800
because I'm not a member of that unit, and they tried to throw me out of the dark over here.

57:58.800 --> 58:08.800
This is probably one of the most dramatic pictures of the Earth that shows auroral belt on the dark side.

58:08.800 --> 58:11.800
You're looking at the Earth with the sun off to your right.

58:11.800 --> 58:18.800
The south pole of the Earth is down, and that funny lip-like thing sticking off to the left at the bottom

58:18.800 --> 58:22.800
is aurora, we think, around the south magnetic pole.

58:22.800 --> 58:31.800
The most striking thing is the next lip up, which on the original you can see better than on this slide,

58:31.800 --> 58:33.800
goes around the full backside of the Earth.

58:33.800 --> 58:43.800
It's called the equatorial auroral belt, and disappears back of the dark side in the upper left corner.

58:43.800 --> 58:47.800
The third lip is another belt.

58:47.800 --> 58:52.800
It looks at first as if that was just all one, but there are two separate belts there,

58:52.800 --> 58:54.800
and it was quite unexpected.

58:54.800 --> 58:55.800
This photo...

58:55.800 --> 58:58.800
What's the dimension of the Earth's actual size?

58:58.800 --> 59:00.800
Well, you know, it's 8,000 miles cross.

59:00.800 --> 59:14.800
There's some halation here, and I guess I'm not too sure, and perhaps George knows.

59:14.800 --> 59:19.800
This is a special Eastman NTB3 emulsion, very, very thin.

59:19.800 --> 59:23.800
And, of course, the exposure was made with electrons, not with light.

59:23.800 --> 59:25.800
It's an electronographic camera.

59:25.800 --> 59:28.800
But the dimension works out right.

59:28.800 --> 59:31.800
You can't see it too well on this print.

59:31.800 --> 59:39.800
There's a ring or a limit to the field, which on the originals is 30 millimeters across.

59:39.800 --> 59:44.800
It's 20 degrees in the sky, and the Earth is 2 degrees, and it checks out.

59:44.800 --> 59:51.800
So the dimension you see there is 2 degrees across the full diameter of the Earth.

59:51.800 --> 59:54.800
You say this is the equatorial auroral belt.

59:54.800 --> 59:58.800
I think what I'm trying to say is that what is the third line from the bottom?

59:58.800 --> 01:00:00.800
Is that the back side you see, or...?

01:00:00.800 --> 01:00:01.800
No, you can't see through the Earth.

01:00:01.800 --> 01:00:02.800
That's why I asked you.

01:00:02.800 --> 01:00:04.800
Is the Earth's the power of the Earth?

01:00:04.800 --> 01:00:05.800
No.

01:00:05.800 --> 01:00:10.800
The geometry is such that that is probably inclined 30 degrees to the magnetic equator,

01:00:10.800 --> 01:00:13.800
and is an unexpected auroral belt.

01:00:13.800 --> 01:00:17.800
It'll take a little more figuring to figure this out.

01:00:17.800 --> 01:00:20.800
What was the latitude of that third belt?

01:00:20.800 --> 01:00:25.800
As I just said, my guess, looking at the picture, it hasn't been measured accurately,

01:00:25.800 --> 01:00:27.800
it's 30 degrees north.

01:00:27.800 --> 01:00:31.800
That's just the standard of bio gas realm.

01:00:31.800 --> 01:00:33.800
Okay.

01:00:33.800 --> 01:00:39.800
You'll notice on these pictures that they're overprinted.

01:00:39.800 --> 01:00:42.800
That's because I'm not a member of the Photographers' Union,

01:00:42.800 --> 01:00:46.800
and the originals have a good deal more on them.

01:00:46.800 --> 01:00:51.800
This picture was taken excluding hydrogen light, Lyman Alpha.

01:00:51.800 --> 01:00:59.800
We have two filters on the camera, and this one is taken in light between the wavelengths of 12, 30, and 1550 angstroms.

01:00:59.800 --> 01:01:00.800
Now, the next slide.

01:01:00.800 --> 01:01:01.800
Can I start?

01:01:01.800 --> 01:01:02.800
Yeah.

01:01:02.800 --> 01:01:07.800
Is the whole diameter you're seeing there, is that all the Earth, or is that twice what the Earth is?

01:01:07.800 --> 01:01:08.800
No, it's the Earth.

01:01:08.800 --> 01:01:09.800
Just the Earth.

01:01:09.800 --> 01:01:10.800
The whole thing you're seeing is the Earth.

01:01:10.800 --> 01:01:11.800
Right.

01:01:11.800 --> 01:01:14.800
Is that twice the image?

01:01:14.800 --> 01:01:15.800
No, no.

01:01:15.800 --> 01:01:21.800
It's, as I said, the little halation, which makes it a little bigger than it ought to be.

01:01:21.800 --> 01:01:22.800
It's only a few percent.

01:01:22.800 --> 01:01:24.800
Yeah, a few percent.

01:01:24.800 --> 01:01:26.800
Now, in this one, it's exactly the same view.

01:01:26.800 --> 01:01:30.800
It was taken after John so accurately pointed the camera at the Earth.

01:01:30.800 --> 01:01:35.800
The Earth is in the middle there, and if you look real hard, you can see the dark side of it off to your left.

01:01:35.800 --> 01:01:37.800
This is the geocorona.

01:01:37.800 --> 01:01:41.800
The streaks are an instrumental matter.

01:01:41.800 --> 01:01:53.800
Actually, we have a barrier membrane that George put very close in front of the film to keep visible light from getting in there.

01:01:53.800 --> 01:01:57.800
And the barrier membrane wasn't quite uniform, and that's where the streaks come from.

01:01:57.800 --> 01:02:01.800
The circular thing on the right is an overlap, another defect.

01:02:01.800 --> 01:02:07.800
The little motor that advanced the film between exposures didn't pull it quite far enough for this one.

01:02:07.800 --> 01:02:13.800
And those dust spikes, I guess, are my pipe tobacco on the slide.

01:02:13.800 --> 01:02:19.800
You know, Thornton, that Rastley thing was moving.

01:02:19.800 --> 01:02:23.800
And at first it wasn't moving.

01:02:23.800 --> 01:02:25.800
The wheels weren't going as far as they did toward the end.

01:02:25.800 --> 01:02:26.800
Yeah.

01:02:26.800 --> 01:02:28.800
No, we have a complete transcript of everything you said about it.

01:02:28.800 --> 01:02:29.800
Okay.

01:02:29.800 --> 01:02:41.800
And in looking at the film, which I've done in great detail, you can see the most serious defect in that film advance was during your short exposures on the Earth, John.

01:02:41.800 --> 01:02:43.800
Everywhere else it worked fine.

01:02:43.800 --> 01:02:55.800
And I have an idea that pushing the buttons so frequently sort of confused the motor, and it didn't turn as far as it should have.

01:02:55.800 --> 01:03:02.800
Well, in any case, you'll notice that the shape of the geocorona is as predicted by Dr. Meyer at the Naval Research Lab.

01:03:02.800 --> 01:03:05.800
It's got a dimple in the back, down sun.

01:03:05.800 --> 01:03:07.800
The sun is still to the right here.

01:03:07.800 --> 01:03:14.800
And our other photographs show that it extends at least twice as far as you see here off to the right.

01:03:14.800 --> 01:03:17.800
The print, of course, can be printed dark or light.

01:03:17.800 --> 01:03:26.800
And if I printed this one lighter, I'd have got the background all over the whole slide, and you wouldn't have been able to see as pretty a picture as this.

01:03:26.800 --> 01:03:31.800
Now, the next slide shows the one further to the right.

01:03:31.800 --> 01:03:32.800
The sun is still to your right.

01:03:32.800 --> 01:03:35.800
The Earth now is off the edge of the picture to the left.

01:03:35.800 --> 01:03:43.800
This was one of the sequence taken through the night between EBAs 2 and 3.

01:03:43.800 --> 01:03:45.800
You see a star background here.

01:03:45.800 --> 01:03:54.800
And again, the geocorona, those streaks which are not real, extending actually right across this frame,

01:03:54.800 --> 01:03:57.800
if you print the thing lighter.

01:03:57.800 --> 01:04:01.800
Now, the next slide shows the two of these combined.

01:04:01.800 --> 01:04:03.800
And that printed a lot darker.

01:04:03.800 --> 01:04:07.800
And I guess it's not as artistic an effort as I had hoped.

01:04:07.800 --> 01:04:18.800
The geocorona produces hydrogen in 1216 angstroms, lina alpha.

01:04:18.800 --> 01:04:23.800
And the next slide shows the spectrum actually taken on that first slide.

01:04:23.800 --> 01:04:27.800
The spectrum is, dispersion is vertical.

01:04:27.800 --> 01:04:32.800
And that white band across horizontally, roughly horizontally, is lina alpha.

01:04:32.800 --> 01:04:33.800
And you see how strong it is.

01:04:33.800 --> 01:04:41.800
The Earth is in the middle of this picture, and the spectrum of the upper atmosphere is spread out on that vertical line,

01:04:41.800 --> 01:04:49.800
from far ultraviolet down at the bottom to nearer ultraviolet up at the top.

01:04:49.800 --> 01:04:55.800
A bright line just above lina alpha is 1304, which is the oxygen line.

01:04:55.800 --> 01:04:58.800
And George, do you want to describe this in a little more detail?

01:04:58.800 --> 01:05:11.800
We've, so far, only made a very crude analysis of the spectra by comparison with the laboratory spectra made in the preflight calibrations.

01:05:11.800 --> 01:05:27.800
However, we have tentatively identified the 584 line of helium, the 834 line of ionized oxygen, the 1026 line of limon beta of hydrogen,

01:05:27.800 --> 01:05:34.800
these three lines are the first spectral measurements in the Earth's upper atmosphere.

01:05:34.800 --> 01:05:40.800
All previous measurements have been limited to wavelengths longward of 1,100 angstroms,

01:05:40.800 --> 01:05:50.800
which we also cover and which includes the Lyman alpha line in 1216, the 1304 and 1356 lines of atomic oxygen,

01:05:50.800 --> 01:06:00.800
and the Lyman-Berge-Hopfield bands of molecular nitrogen between 1,200 and 1,600 angstroms.

01:06:00.800 --> 01:06:06.800
The Lyman alpha line, of course, is by far the strongest emission that we have seen in any of our spectra,

01:06:06.800 --> 01:06:12.800
and it's the only one that we have conclusively identified in any of the spectra that do not include the Earth.

01:06:12.800 --> 01:06:20.800
However, by comparison of spectra taken with and without our lithium fluoride corrector plate, which cuts off at 1050 angstroms,

01:06:20.800 --> 01:06:31.800
we will be able to determine whether we see a general background in the 584 line of helium and the 1026 line of atomic oxygen hydrogen,

01:06:31.800 --> 01:06:36.800
as we expect, though they will be much weaker than the Lyman alpha line.

01:06:36.800 --> 01:06:39.800
We've got that other spectrum coming.

01:06:39.800 --> 01:06:41.800
In other words, can you hold on a minute?

01:06:41.800 --> 01:06:46.800
I think the order he's got him in has the Magellanic cloud, and we're probably taking too much time.

01:06:46.800 --> 01:06:49.800
Can we have the next slide?

01:06:49.800 --> 01:06:51.800
Oh, that's it. Go ahead.

01:06:51.800 --> 01:06:55.800
So this is without the corrector plate.

01:06:55.800 --> 01:06:59.800
You'll notice that the Lyman alpha here is broader.

01:06:59.800 --> 01:07:08.800
The definition is poorer, but as George was just saying, we get lines further down in the ultraviolet on spectra

01:07:08.800 --> 01:07:10.800
taken without the corrector plate than with it.

01:07:10.800 --> 01:07:14.800
And you see here, too, these other lines are not uniform.

01:07:14.800 --> 01:07:19.800
This is a spectrum that was obtained with the Earth off the edge here.

01:07:19.800 --> 01:07:24.800
So it shows that the geochrona goes right across this slide, as I said last time.

01:07:24.800 --> 01:07:26.800
By the way, that's 100,000 miles.

01:07:26.800 --> 01:07:33.800
And the other lines here show that either other materials in the geochrona or beyond the geochrona.

01:07:33.800 --> 01:07:38.800
I guess it's going to take a little while to figure out which are which.

01:07:38.800 --> 01:07:40.800
Go ahead. I didn't get a question.

01:07:40.800 --> 01:07:42.800
Is that any more to say about it?

01:07:42.800 --> 01:07:43.800
I guess, yes.

01:07:43.800 --> 01:07:46.800
The next two slides quickly show the, well, that's right.

01:07:46.800 --> 01:07:47.800
It's one.

01:07:47.800 --> 01:07:52.800
The Magellanic Clouds, which are, well, John was worried about what LNC meant,

01:07:52.800 --> 01:07:57.800
and this is the Large Magellanic Cloud, and that's the initial, what the initials referred to.

01:07:57.800 --> 01:08:01.800
The picture on the left is with hydrogen, with lamin alpha.

01:08:01.800 --> 01:08:04.800
And the picture on the right is without.

01:08:04.800 --> 01:08:11.800
In this far ultraviolet region, all that you are seeing here are the very hot blue stars.

01:08:11.800 --> 01:08:15.800
And over here you see the clouds of hydrogen gas.

01:08:15.800 --> 01:08:18.800
So the difference between these two photographs is hydrogen.

01:08:18.800 --> 01:08:23.800
And we get the record of, well, the Magellanic Clouds are nearby galaxies,

01:08:23.800 --> 01:08:28.800
so we have a galaxy with all of the stars and neutrons and whatnot spread out in front of us to study.

01:08:28.800 --> 01:08:36.800
Now, Carl Hennei has made special studies of these Magellanic Clouds and is very much interested

01:08:36.800 --> 01:08:40.800
and already has copies of these photographs for the study.

01:08:40.800 --> 01:08:45.800
You notice that the hydrogen is not just from the Magellanic Clouds.

01:08:45.800 --> 01:08:52.800
The stuff up here is out in the open sky, and just what caused that background, I don't know.

01:08:52.800 --> 01:08:57.800
Is there any other slide?

01:08:57.800 --> 01:09:01.800
That's the last one.

01:09:01.800 --> 01:09:04.800
We had a couple of questions for John.

01:09:04.800 --> 01:09:06.800
One was that sticking which had us worried.

01:09:06.800 --> 01:09:11.800
You talked about the instrument may flying Apollo 17.

01:09:11.800 --> 01:09:17.800
Robert, it's very Houston in it.

01:09:17.800 --> 01:09:20.800
So what was the sticking?

01:09:20.800 --> 01:09:21.800
Did it continue right through?

01:09:21.800 --> 01:09:23.800
You didn't mention it in EVA-3.

01:09:23.800 --> 01:09:25.800
It got worse all along.

01:09:25.800 --> 01:09:38.800
I just got the feeling there was some kind of hang-up in possibly long-term vacuum exposure

01:09:38.800 --> 01:09:45.800
or something to the operation of the way it was working in azimuth.

01:09:45.800 --> 01:09:50.800
And I never was able to, or never able to really...

01:09:50.800 --> 01:09:51.800
It never got better.

01:09:51.800 --> 01:09:52.800
No, it never got better.

01:09:52.800 --> 01:10:00.800
In fact, the longer it sat there, maybe the cold, it just seemed to get stickier and stickier.

01:10:00.800 --> 01:10:06.800
Toward the end there, every time I had to, every time I got to a new setting in azimuth,

01:10:06.800 --> 01:10:10.800
it completely destroyed the level.

01:10:10.800 --> 01:10:17.800
And we were unfortunate that we were on that slope right there under the foot pad of the limb.

01:10:17.800 --> 01:10:22.800
And so I had to go back and re-level it every time.

01:10:22.800 --> 01:10:34.800
And that was, we were really working at the limits of the level ability of the machinery, I think, there.

01:10:34.800 --> 01:10:36.800
You see that it didn't make much difference.

01:10:36.800 --> 01:10:38.800
That Magellanic Cloud should have been out in the middle.

01:10:38.800 --> 01:10:39.800
I know, I know.

01:10:39.800 --> 01:10:41.800
And you were off by that much because...

01:10:41.800 --> 01:10:45.800
But, well, that's...

01:10:45.800 --> 01:10:50.800
If we were on a level slope, there would have been no problem in getting a bubble right in the middle every time.

01:10:50.800 --> 01:10:56.800
And if the azimuth had worked easily, it would have remained level.

01:10:56.800 --> 01:10:58.800
But I sure don't know what it was.

01:10:58.800 --> 01:11:01.800
It couldn't have been dust that got in the...

01:11:01.800 --> 01:11:03.800
We thought that was impossible.

01:11:03.800 --> 01:11:05.800
No, I don't think we had any...

01:11:05.800 --> 01:11:12.800
In fact, I'm sure we didn't have any dust on the legs up that far.

01:11:12.800 --> 01:11:16.800
The film cassette you brought back had very little dust on it.

01:11:16.800 --> 01:11:18.800
In fact, it looked brand new.

01:11:18.800 --> 01:11:19.800
Well, I hope...

01:11:19.800 --> 01:11:22.800
If it got dust on it, it got it inside the limb.

01:11:22.800 --> 01:11:25.800
There was plenty in there once we got into zero gravity.

01:11:25.800 --> 01:11:28.800
Although, I don't know how to crawl through two bags.

01:11:28.800 --> 01:11:31.800
That's why I was quite surprised there was no dust in the bag.

01:11:31.800 --> 01:11:35.800
In fact, we're disappointed because we're going to collect a little bit of dust off it.

01:11:35.800 --> 01:11:36.800
I know.

01:11:36.800 --> 01:11:38.800
Any questions on the floor?

01:11:38.800 --> 01:11:39.800
Yes.

01:11:39.800 --> 01:11:43.800
And I'm sure it got some dust on it when I removed it, though.

01:11:43.800 --> 01:11:45.800
Well, I got a little...

01:11:45.800 --> 01:11:49.800
A very small amount, which I'm legally keeping it with this.

01:11:49.800 --> 01:11:51.800
Don't tell anybody.

01:11:51.800 --> 01:11:54.800
The FBI will be around to see you.

01:11:54.800 --> 01:11:58.800
Did you see evidence of the magneto sheet or a bow shot?

01:11:58.800 --> 01:12:06.800
So far, we have not seen any discontinuity in the up-sun geocorona, which would be indicative of that.

01:12:06.800 --> 01:12:08.800
It just sort of dribbles off the way.

01:12:08.800 --> 01:12:12.800
As you go sunward from the Earth, then there's no sharp drop.

01:12:12.800 --> 01:12:15.800
But we're really not as far as the...

01:12:15.800 --> 01:12:19.800
Ten or the radiation should have been in the middle of that up-sun.

01:12:19.800 --> 01:12:20.800
I know.

01:12:20.800 --> 01:12:21.800
I guess...

01:12:21.800 --> 01:12:22.800
Is it only...

01:12:22.800 --> 01:12:23.800
There's only ten.

01:12:23.800 --> 01:12:24.800
Twelve.

01:12:24.800 --> 01:12:25.800
Yeah.

01:12:25.800 --> 01:12:26.800
Okay.

01:12:26.800 --> 01:12:28.800
Any more questions?

01:12:28.800 --> 01:12:29.800
Okay.

01:12:29.800 --> 01:12:34.800
Next subject is the lunar geology investigation.

01:12:34.800 --> 01:12:35.800
Dr. Mulverter.

01:12:35.800 --> 01:12:36.800
Dr. Mulverter.

01:12:36.800 --> 01:12:37.800
Dr. Mulverter.

01:12:37.800 --> 01:12:38.800
Dr. Mulverter.

01:12:38.800 --> 01:12:39.800
Dr. Mulverter.

01:12:39.800 --> 01:13:01.800
For the benefit of the astrologer in the crowd, there's been very little evidence for water, and none so far for geysers.

01:13:01.800 --> 01:13:14.800
Our experiment may not be as far-reaching as theirs, but on the other hand, I think we've made a large step toward understanding the history of the moon, and therefore the Earth, and therefore the solar system.

01:13:14.800 --> 01:13:19.800
And if you guys can find any more, we're out there with you.

01:13:19.800 --> 01:13:33.800
So far, we've completed the mission itself, and all major objectives for the preplanned traverses were reached, and were sampled, and were described, and photographed.

01:13:33.800 --> 01:13:38.800
And as far as we can tell with our quick look at the photographs, all of these were done well.

01:13:38.800 --> 01:13:48.800
We've produced a so-called greenback at the end of the mission operations itself, which was a summary as of our knowledge at that time.

01:13:48.800 --> 01:13:52.800
It was based on crew observations, TV, and the pre-mission data.

01:13:52.800 --> 01:14:02.800
Included in that thing are station sample maps, which were derived from the TV in real time, and that was a very useful tool to us.

01:14:02.800 --> 01:14:11.800
A sample inventory, a film usage inventory, and a station locations, again, resected from the TV pans.

01:14:11.800 --> 01:14:20.800
By the end of last week, we've received black and white two-time enlargements of all film.

01:14:20.800 --> 01:14:29.800
These are the typical drugstore-quality prints, and sooner or later, we'll get good quality, so our analysis is very brief.

01:14:29.800 --> 01:14:31.800
We've assembled all the panoramas.

01:14:31.800 --> 01:14:35.800
Sample location studies are nearing completion.

01:14:35.800 --> 01:14:39.800
The film inventory is also nearing completion.

01:14:39.800 --> 01:14:47.800
The geological analysis is still in its infancy, and I suspect it should progress rapidly now that we've got all this inventorying over with.

01:14:47.800 --> 01:14:53.800
You guys took so damn many pictures, it takes time to get them organized.

01:14:53.800 --> 01:15:01.800
We've had one session with the crew in the LRL with samples, and most of our questions need samples in hand,

01:15:01.800 --> 01:15:06.800
and those I'm sure we'll be able to discuss later.

01:15:06.800 --> 01:15:12.800
And so the questions I've got relate more to surface observations that maybe we can amplify.

01:15:12.800 --> 01:15:22.800
And some of these are questions that we've asked you before, but I have a few polaroid prints of these photos that maybe can jostle our minds,

01:15:22.800 --> 01:15:34.800
and assist in refining some of the answers that we've gotten on the debriefs after the EVAs or on trans-Earth.

01:15:34.800 --> 01:15:40.800
Our photo-geological mapping group primarily talked about rays by their whiteness.

01:15:40.800 --> 01:15:44.800
There were a few spots where they thought they were seeing dark rays.

01:15:44.800 --> 01:15:50.800
You recognize both light and dark colored rays, particularly the south ray picture.

01:15:50.800 --> 01:16:04.800
If I could have slide one, please, which is the south ray panorama and the print I've just given to the crew a single frame from that.

01:16:04.800 --> 01:16:14.800
There I think we can see light and dark, and the real question I'm after is what led you to say that you were on or off a ray?

01:16:14.800 --> 01:16:24.800
And secondly, were there any visible differences in the rock types as you drove by or had a chance of sampling ray material?

01:16:24.800 --> 01:16:34.800
The hills are at the bottom.

01:16:34.800 --> 01:16:39.800
Yeah, I think the thumbprint goes in the upper right.

01:16:39.800 --> 01:16:46.800
Could the projectionist give that a 180, please, around a horizontal axis?

01:16:46.800 --> 01:16:50.800
That one's got the same problem. There we go.

01:16:50.800 --> 01:16:55.800
Now it's a hill instead of a hole.

01:16:55.800 --> 01:16:59.800
This is your pan from Station 4.

01:16:59.800 --> 01:17:04.800
You see that black line coming over the...

01:17:04.800 --> 01:17:08.800
This photo really doesn't do that same justice.

01:17:08.800 --> 01:17:10.800
Polaroid prints never do.

01:17:10.800 --> 01:17:14.800
Well, I mean, you really have to see it to believe it.

01:17:14.800 --> 01:17:23.800
That white is so much whiter than the contrast that we were able to get out of the photographs.

01:17:23.800 --> 01:17:33.800
I think when I looked at it, my assessment of this, which is kind of a bad place, was that it was a black ray coming out.

01:17:33.800 --> 01:17:36.800
The right rim there on the photograph.

01:17:36.800 --> 01:17:44.800
And it probably went right down that, as you know, the photograph that showed the black area coming out of South Ray.

01:17:44.800 --> 01:17:45.800
Right.

01:17:45.800 --> 01:17:48.800
And there's a series of black blocks.

01:17:48.800 --> 01:17:50.800
There's a bunch right there.

01:17:50.800 --> 01:17:51.800
Left edge.

01:17:51.800 --> 01:17:52.800
Yeah.

01:17:52.800 --> 01:17:54.800
And there's also...

01:17:54.800 --> 01:17:56.800
And Charlie described this in real time.

01:17:56.800 --> 01:18:01.800
There's some more black blocks in there.

01:18:01.800 --> 01:18:04.800
And they seem to come out in ray patterns, too.

01:18:04.800 --> 01:18:06.800
Don't you think, Charlie?

01:18:06.800 --> 01:18:07.800
Yeah.

01:18:07.800 --> 01:18:08.800
That rascally...

01:18:08.800 --> 01:18:10.800
That's one spectacular crater.

01:18:10.800 --> 01:18:19.800
That ray coming down the south right edge might have been the ray that made, or at least part of it, that made Survey Ridge.

01:18:19.800 --> 01:18:27.800
Because it just ran right across those wrecked trap craters, and we could see it going all the way down.

01:18:27.800 --> 01:18:30.800
Is that the bright ray you're talking about in the lower right?

01:18:30.800 --> 01:18:35.800
This ray right here, Bill, came right through Stubby, right up over, and right out of Survey Ridge.

01:18:35.800 --> 01:18:36.800
This one right here.

01:18:36.800 --> 01:18:39.800
So that was the source of your terrific block field there.

01:18:39.800 --> 01:18:40.800
Oh, man.

01:18:40.800 --> 01:18:44.800
And just amazing how much rocks a rascal laid down.

01:18:44.800 --> 01:18:47.800
I just couldn't believe it.

01:18:47.800 --> 01:18:51.800
Traffic ability in close to that thing would probably have been very interesting.

01:18:51.800 --> 01:18:54.800
We should have had another EVA to find out.

01:18:54.800 --> 01:18:58.800
I think it's a heat flow one.

01:18:58.800 --> 01:19:05.800
The reason we called we were on a ray was really an abundance of secondary craters and an abundance of blocks.

01:19:05.800 --> 01:19:18.800
And they thinned and thickened as we, I think, traverse raised, but we never did get totally out of blocks to the south, to the traverse to the south.

01:19:18.800 --> 01:19:32.800
There were always five, at least three to five percent of the surface had cobbles, and I say cobbles, 20 centimeter blocks, and larger.

01:19:32.800 --> 01:19:44.800
And the blocks were generally asymmetrical enough to the crater, or the crater shape was elongated, or just a great spattering of craters is why you're calling them secondaries?

01:19:44.800 --> 01:19:49.800
I think subjectively we felt they were oriented from south ray all the time.

01:19:49.800 --> 01:19:50.800
Right.

01:19:50.800 --> 01:19:53.800
It was really just a subjective field as we were driving by them.

01:19:53.800 --> 01:19:57.800
There were a lot of the blocks that were not associated with any craters.

01:19:57.800 --> 01:20:05.800
There would be a pile of a series of secondaries, but around for a couple of hundred meters, there'd be more blocks.

01:20:05.800 --> 01:20:11.800
In fact, as far as you could see, there'd be blocks just scattered over the surface that were not associated with any secondaries.

01:20:11.800 --> 01:20:23.800
But the true secondaries were, we did see some that were classic, where they were, you could, the ejector was down range from, and it pointed right to the south ray.

01:20:23.800 --> 01:20:26.800
Station four, for instance, was one that was...

01:20:26.800 --> 01:20:29.800
Can I have slide four, please?

01:20:29.800 --> 01:20:38.800
I might add that these black rays and the black blocks that you see here were also evident at baby ray.

01:20:38.800 --> 01:20:40.800
Can you rotate that one, too?

01:20:40.800 --> 01:20:53.800
And to a more, or to a lesser degree, the sampling at north ray had an appearance of being black and white matrixed, black and white rocks also.

01:20:53.800 --> 01:20:54.800
The north ray rocks.

01:20:54.800 --> 01:21:00.800
Do these black streaks go all into the crater themselves, down vertically down into the sides of the crater?

01:21:00.800 --> 01:21:07.800
At south ray, yeah. That one on the left that you saw there was, you could track it over the rim and back right across the rim.

01:21:07.800 --> 01:21:12.800
And Ken, could you see that from orbit? You can see a lot of these fresh, but like black streak craters.

01:21:12.800 --> 01:21:24.800
This one, south ray does not have nearly the obvious dark streaks that run down inside and outside that many of the other craters do.

01:21:24.800 --> 01:21:29.800
There was dark material, dark appearing material, it was very obvious, in the crater interior.

01:21:29.800 --> 01:21:35.800
But I never recognized it as being a ray that was thrown out with a radial dimension.

01:21:35.800 --> 01:21:43.800
Yeah, I think, looking at the photography, the feeling we got from looking at south ray was that that black streak was just an absence of any rays.

01:21:43.800 --> 01:21:52.800
But I think, from the blocks, it must be black ray material.

01:21:52.800 --> 01:21:53.800
Dark material.

01:21:53.800 --> 01:21:57.800
Maybe the dark matrix rocks would produce that darkening.

01:21:57.800 --> 01:22:01.800
It petered out a lot faster than the white rays, though.

01:22:01.800 --> 01:22:04.800
So, I mean, you know, within a quarter of a crater diameter.

01:22:04.800 --> 01:22:06.800
Yeah, I think it was from the bottom of it.

01:22:06.800 --> 01:22:08.800
From the bottom of it.

01:22:08.800 --> 01:22:11.800
Those could disappear just because of their general appearance.

01:22:11.800 --> 01:22:12.800
Could.

01:22:12.800 --> 01:22:19.800
Like the local regolith, the white ones being so obviously different, it would be easier to recognize.

01:22:19.800 --> 01:22:23.800
I suspect why the mappers did the same thing.

01:22:23.800 --> 01:22:28.800
Here's your pan, John, or part of it, looking up sun.

01:22:28.800 --> 01:22:31.800
And this crater you suggested was the secondary.

01:22:31.800 --> 01:22:38.800
And therefore, the sampling that you were doing primarily over there to the left corner is where the rover is,

01:22:38.800 --> 01:22:42.800
would be south ray ejecta as the principal source.

01:22:42.800 --> 01:22:51.800
There's one reason we wanted to move you on, and I think that was a good decision now that we look at your photographs and from what you had told us.

01:22:51.800 --> 01:23:03.800
Well, we sampled this crater up on this close-in rim and down the rim a little bit, but I, man, if that's not a classic secondary, I never saw one.

01:23:03.800 --> 01:23:08.800
That's type locality, if you pardon the geological verbiage.

01:23:08.800 --> 01:23:12.800
And you can see the debris from there. It's scattered all out in here, too.

01:23:12.800 --> 01:23:13.800
The rover's back over here.

01:23:13.800 --> 01:23:14.800
Yes.

01:23:14.800 --> 01:23:15.800
Down slope.

01:23:15.800 --> 01:23:17.800
You can see it right in the left corner, just the edge of it.

01:23:17.800 --> 01:23:18.800
Oh, yeah.

01:23:18.800 --> 01:23:21.800
And I think you're standing there, Charlie.

01:23:21.800 --> 01:23:23.800
Probably on my face.

01:23:26.800 --> 01:23:27.800
Okay.

01:23:30.800 --> 01:23:37.800
Okay, related to this are some of the craters that you called indurated and had clods around them.

01:23:38.800 --> 01:23:41.800
Can I have photo seven, please?

01:23:41.800 --> 01:23:44.800
And that'll probably need a 180, too.

01:23:50.800 --> 01:23:51.800
No, plumb.

01:23:51.800 --> 01:23:52.800
No, number seven.

01:23:52.800 --> 01:23:53.800
Oh, yeah, that's plumb.

01:23:53.800 --> 01:23:54.800
Okay.

01:23:54.800 --> 01:24:00.800
Now, that plumb's got a little bench in it, and on the pre-mission work, there were quite a lot of them that had benches

01:24:00.800 --> 01:24:09.800
suggested that there was an indurated layer that was shallow compared to what the crater counts said that the age of that whole surface had to be.

01:24:09.800 --> 01:24:19.800
We just heard Kovacs tell us there's a very thick regolith here, which is what it should have had by the cratering stories, and yet there was always this little bench.

01:24:19.800 --> 01:24:38.800
We're wondering now whether that bench has some relationship to the ejecta from the south ray and north ray craters, and therefore might be what you've brought up here on the rim of plumb as some of the pre-ray indurated regolith.

01:24:38.800 --> 01:24:44.800
Do you have any thoughts that could go into that?

01:24:44.800 --> 01:24:47.800
That wasn't what I was calling the indurated regolith, Phil.

01:24:47.800 --> 01:24:48.800
Wasn't it?

01:24:48.800 --> 01:24:49.800
No.

01:24:49.800 --> 01:24:50.800
What was that?

01:24:50.800 --> 01:24:55.800
The indurated regolith I was talking about was two-meter-sized craters.

01:24:55.800 --> 01:24:56.800
Two-meter.

01:24:56.800 --> 01:25:13.800
Yeah, two-meter-sized, and there were little teeny clods, no bigger than a grapefruit, and that were symmetrically around a very shallow crater that had a hackly black glass right in the center of these little craters.

01:25:13.800 --> 01:25:16.800
And the biggest one was no more than two meters in.

01:25:16.800 --> 01:25:21.800
You see down in the plumb, see that outline of rocks down in there?

01:25:21.800 --> 01:25:22.800
No, keep going down.

01:25:22.800 --> 01:25:23.800
Right here?

01:25:23.800 --> 01:25:24.800
No, over here.

01:25:24.800 --> 01:25:25.800
To the left.

01:25:25.800 --> 01:25:26.800
Okay.

01:25:26.800 --> 01:25:30.800
See those rocks right in there?

01:25:30.800 --> 01:25:31.800
I think...

01:25:31.800 --> 01:25:33.800
Near the bottom of the view.

01:25:33.800 --> 01:25:55.800
I wouldn't be surprised, but what the most likely candidate for a rock that was from down either in the bottom of plumb or from the lower part of flag was that piece of rock that we chipped off of.

01:25:55.800 --> 01:25:56.800
It's located right in this area.

01:25:56.800 --> 01:26:01.800
Yeah, it's just outside of the view of the picture.

01:26:01.800 --> 01:26:02.800
And I...

01:26:02.800 --> 01:26:04.800
Because that had been...

01:26:04.800 --> 01:26:05.800
That was well under the...

01:26:05.800 --> 01:26:12.800
I mean, it was a submerged rock, and I got the feeling that it was sort of local to the area.

01:26:12.800 --> 01:26:19.800
I mean, I don't see how it could have been from South Ray or unless that was extremely soft when it plunked in there.

01:26:19.800 --> 01:26:24.800
I didn't rule out that, but I mean, that would be the most likely candidate of the ones we could get to.

01:26:24.800 --> 01:26:25.800
We could...

01:26:25.800 --> 01:26:29.800
There's no way we could have got down in there and got those rocks.

01:26:29.800 --> 01:26:30.800
That's true.

01:26:30.800 --> 01:26:31.800
And gotten back.

01:26:31.800 --> 01:26:39.800
Since they took your tether away from you, I don't imagine you want to explore those craters.

01:26:39.800 --> 01:26:44.800
Okay, the Buster Crater...

01:26:44.800 --> 01:26:47.800
Photo 8, please.

01:26:47.800 --> 01:26:54.800
This is your partial pan of Buster.

01:26:54.800 --> 01:26:58.800
Again, not a winner for photographic work.

01:26:58.800 --> 01:27:02.800
It's at least as good as the astrologer's pictures, though.

01:27:02.800 --> 01:27:10.800
You described that there was a southwest and northeast bouldery field in here.

01:27:10.800 --> 01:27:13.800
We're looking almost down the sun, and I'm wondering...

01:27:13.800 --> 01:27:15.800
I can't tell in these photographs.

01:27:15.800 --> 01:27:29.800
Could you tell whether there are blocks over in there, and therefore your impression of this streak across it could not be salted because you're looking down sun?

01:27:29.800 --> 01:27:31.800
Well, I might have been...

01:27:31.800 --> 01:27:34.800
I didn't really mean to say southeast-northwest.

01:27:34.800 --> 01:27:35.800
This...

01:27:35.800 --> 01:27:46.800
The predominance of blocks in Buster were oriented in this direction, across out this way, which is northeast-southwest.

01:27:46.800 --> 01:27:47.800
Yeah.

01:27:47.800 --> 01:27:48.800
And...

01:27:48.800 --> 01:27:49.800
That's what you said.

01:27:49.800 --> 01:27:50.800
Yeah.

01:27:50.800 --> 01:27:51.800
And...

01:27:51.800 --> 01:27:52.800
You're reconfirming that.

01:27:52.800 --> 01:27:53.800
Reconfirm that.

01:27:53.800 --> 01:27:58.800
And over in this area, you can see some of the blocks, but not nearly as many as here.

01:27:58.800 --> 01:28:14.800
Now, we can barely see the bottom of Buster, but the bottom of Buster is covered with blocks that were up to two meters across, and showed no orientation in any direction.

01:28:14.800 --> 01:28:18.800
My feeling over here, due to the...

01:28:18.800 --> 01:28:21.800
There were blocks in this area, but they're not...

01:28:21.800 --> 01:28:26.800
They were not as numerous as this pattern in here.

01:28:26.800 --> 01:28:27.800
All right.

01:28:27.800 --> 01:28:39.800
So the blocks that you're... on the side you were standing would have been derived primarily from that hole, and not from the impacting material that...

01:28:39.800 --> 01:28:43.800
It has the appearance of a secondary from South Ray in this kind of a photograph.

01:28:43.800 --> 01:28:44.800
Sure.

01:28:44.800 --> 01:28:47.800
Your description of it, do you not go with that interpretation?

01:28:47.800 --> 01:28:49.800
Well, if it is, it's the biggest one that we saw.

01:28:49.800 --> 01:28:50.800
It's a big one.

01:28:50.800 --> 01:28:51.800
That is a big crater.

01:28:51.800 --> 01:28:57.800
From here to here, it was at least 50 meters.

01:28:57.800 --> 01:28:59.800
At least, yeah.

01:28:59.800 --> 01:29:09.800
And the size of those blocks and the depth of that crater, and South Ray is six kilometers away, that had to be one big block that pounded into there.

01:29:09.800 --> 01:29:10.800
Yeah.

01:29:10.800 --> 01:29:13.800
And I don't know whether you can even excavate something that large.

01:29:13.800 --> 01:29:16.800
It's much too large to be...

01:29:16.800 --> 01:29:18.800
I don't really think it's a secondary.

01:29:18.800 --> 01:29:24.800
Well, that's my feeling that looking at it, it was a primary, because I couldn't conceive of how you'd get one from...

01:29:24.800 --> 01:29:29.800
Of course, it could have maybe been a secondary from one of those big craters way down south.

01:29:29.800 --> 01:29:31.800
I think that's a possibility.

01:29:31.800 --> 01:29:32.800
Yeah.

01:29:32.800 --> 01:29:42.800
So that's either local bedrock or some of the flap or the thrown out material from spook that we're seeing there in the floor and the walls.

01:29:42.800 --> 01:29:43.800
Great.

01:29:43.800 --> 01:29:44.800
Spook didn't look like that at all.

01:29:44.800 --> 01:29:46.800
This was a lot fresher crater than spook.

01:29:46.800 --> 01:29:48.800
I hate to oversimplify this business.

01:29:48.800 --> 01:29:49.800
Man, because it...

01:29:49.800 --> 01:29:52.800
Don't tell them where that rascal came from.

01:29:56.800 --> 01:30:01.800
Okay, I'd like to have slide nine, please.

01:30:06.800 --> 01:30:08.800
This is North Ray Crater.

01:30:08.800 --> 01:30:15.800
And there were arguments among you guys and there were arguments among ours as to whether we're seeing layering in there.

01:30:15.800 --> 01:30:20.800
And I think the layering that you were talking about, John, is over in the right part where there's a dominance of blocks.

01:30:20.800 --> 01:30:21.800
Is that...

01:30:21.800 --> 01:30:22.800
Yes, sir.

01:30:22.800 --> 01:30:23.800
...a true statement?

01:30:23.800 --> 01:30:26.800
Right there.

01:30:26.800 --> 01:30:30.800
Yeah, that's certainly one of the best candidates for...

01:30:30.800 --> 01:30:31.800
Yeah, I just...

01:30:31.800 --> 01:30:38.800
It's just hard to imagine how the blocks would either all slump down there and end up at that spot or...

01:30:38.800 --> 01:30:45.800
Yeah, slump down there and end up there.

01:30:45.800 --> 01:30:53.800
You know, in our geology trips we ran across a lot of contacts that was a great deal more subtle than that one right there.

01:30:53.800 --> 01:30:56.800
And that's why I picked it.

01:30:56.800 --> 01:31:01.800
There's a better view of that as you get on further to the north, Bill.

01:31:01.800 --> 01:31:04.800
I think it shows it a little bit deeper down.

01:31:04.800 --> 01:31:05.800
But there's...

01:31:05.800 --> 01:31:07.800
Certainly if there is any...

01:31:07.800 --> 01:31:12.800
The right polarimetric pan is what I should have had rather than the left.

01:31:12.800 --> 01:31:13.800
Okay.

01:31:13.800 --> 01:31:16.800
It was in use when I needed to make the picture.

01:31:16.800 --> 01:31:18.800
You know, up at...

01:31:18.800 --> 01:31:23.800
Going up Stone Mountain there was one other crater that we were looking into as we were driving up Stone Mountain

01:31:23.800 --> 01:31:31.800
where we could see what looked to be more like an outcrop than anything I've seen so far.

01:31:31.800 --> 01:31:35.800
In that it was the same kind of thing, only it wasn't broken up like that.

01:31:35.800 --> 01:31:36.800
It was just one solid piece.

01:31:36.800 --> 01:31:39.800
I don't think there was any way we'd have gotten up the hill to it.

01:31:39.800 --> 01:31:41.800
And we've got some photographs of that.

01:31:41.800 --> 01:31:45.800
And it shows up on a 16mm photography as we're driving up there.

01:31:45.800 --> 01:31:46.800
And I can point it out to you.

01:31:46.800 --> 01:31:54.800
But it was about that, you know, one third of the way down from the top to the floor.

01:31:54.800 --> 01:31:56.800
The same kind of...

01:31:56.800 --> 01:31:58.800
The rover...

01:31:58.800 --> 01:32:02.800
But that's the only two places where I'd really call out...

01:32:02.800 --> 01:32:05.800
I would hazard a guess that that was outcrop.

01:32:05.800 --> 01:32:06.800
That was outcrop.

01:32:06.800 --> 01:32:11.800
Off to the left there, you can see a vertical string of blocks right in the middle.

01:32:11.800 --> 01:32:12.800
Right here?

01:32:12.800 --> 01:32:14.800
The far wall, yeah.

01:32:14.800 --> 01:32:20.800
And were there any visual observations you made of that that...

01:32:20.800 --> 01:32:27.800
Well, again, I got the impression we had areas, white areas, and dark areas.

01:32:27.800 --> 01:32:32.800
Now, maybe the darkening was just because of the shadows caused by the rocks.

01:32:32.800 --> 01:32:37.800
Now, I got the feeling those were the dark blocks like house rock, just like Charlie does.

01:32:37.800 --> 01:32:41.800
And I got the feeling there were places where there were strings of white blocks, too.

01:32:41.800 --> 01:32:44.800
These rocks right here that are more buried are...

01:32:44.800 --> 01:32:49.800
And the regolith is deeper in this area, are all white matrixed rocks.

01:32:49.800 --> 01:32:50.800
Yeah.

01:32:50.800 --> 01:32:56.800
Around this way, and really right out from this little block here, is house rock sits here.

01:32:56.800 --> 01:32:57.800
Right.

01:32:57.800 --> 01:33:00.800
And that is predominantly a black matrixed rock.

01:33:00.800 --> 01:33:06.800
And I counted nine radial block trails out of that crater.

01:33:06.800 --> 01:33:13.800
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, and there's a couple over in here.

01:33:13.800 --> 01:33:18.800
It gave you the impression that you could track them from the floor all the way out over the rim,

01:33:18.800 --> 01:33:22.800
at least as far as we could see.

01:33:22.800 --> 01:33:25.800
Distinct zones of blocks.

01:33:25.800 --> 01:33:26.800
Good.

01:33:26.800 --> 01:33:34.800
As rascally, actual craters don't really exhibit the classic overturned flap that we've been looking at.

01:33:34.800 --> 01:33:39.800
They are more complicated than that when they all get shuffling around on themselves.

01:33:39.800 --> 01:33:46.800
In here, as I said, we had an impression that the regolith was more loosely consolidated

01:33:46.800 --> 01:33:49.800
because of a footprint impression I had.

01:33:49.800 --> 01:33:58.800
Down at South Ray, correction, down at House Rock, we already commented that we couldn't even get the tongs or the shovel,

01:33:58.800 --> 01:33:59.800
or the scoop in.

01:33:59.800 --> 01:34:04.800
And around the rover, which was sitting right back out here, we had the same problem.

01:34:04.800 --> 01:34:09.800
And you don't get the impression from here, but the slope going down to that block where we'd have to go down to

01:34:09.800 --> 01:34:15.800
to get a picture of the bottom of the crater was not the kind of thing I'd want Charlie to be doing

01:34:15.800 --> 01:34:17.800
without having that hundred-foot line on us.

01:34:17.800 --> 01:34:19.800
So we didn't get any pictures of the bottom of it.

01:34:19.800 --> 01:34:25.800
Well, we'll wait until we get the pan camera stuff to look into the bottom, I guess.

01:34:25.800 --> 01:34:27.800
Or Ken's words on it.

01:34:27.800 --> 01:34:31.800
I wouldn't mind him going down there, but I'd like to be able to get him back.

01:34:31.800 --> 01:34:34.800
Yeah, me too.

01:34:34.800 --> 01:34:44.800
As you can see here, the white matrix rocks had more filleted and appeared to be more covered with regolith

01:34:44.800 --> 01:34:51.800
than the larger rocks around over here to the north where the black matrix rocks, the house rock was.

01:34:51.800 --> 01:34:57.800
It had some filleting, but it was not nearly so pronounced as this area up to the south.

01:34:57.800 --> 01:35:02.800
Would the house rock TV pan do you any things you'd want to point at?

01:35:02.800 --> 01:35:05.800
I've got that up there in the slide if you'd want to.

01:35:05.800 --> 01:35:07.800
It's lousy, but it's...

01:35:07.800 --> 01:35:08.800
I don't think so.

01:35:08.800 --> 01:35:10.800
It's a big one.

01:35:10.800 --> 01:35:20.800
I guess it's a quarter of the way down to the bottom.

01:35:20.800 --> 01:35:21.800
Well, it's really hard to tell.

01:35:21.800 --> 01:35:23.800
You know, that rascal is half a mile across.

01:35:23.800 --> 01:35:28.800
So some of those rocks sitting in there must be almost as big as house rock.

01:35:28.800 --> 01:35:29.800
Yeah, that's right.

01:35:29.800 --> 01:35:31.800
It's really hard to say.

01:35:31.800 --> 01:35:37.800
We didn't ever see the bottom, and it's about a quarter of the way down from where we could

01:35:37.800 --> 01:35:39.800
see.

01:35:39.800 --> 01:35:44.800
I would imagine that the bottom of North Ray looks very much like Buster, the bottom of

01:35:44.800 --> 01:35:48.800
Buster, with bigger blocks.

01:35:48.800 --> 01:35:49.800
Yeah.

01:35:49.800 --> 01:35:50.800
Hopefully the pan camera will show that.

01:35:50.800 --> 01:35:51.800
But we never...

01:35:51.800 --> 01:35:52.800
Pre-mission photography.

01:35:52.800 --> 01:35:57.800
You had a feeling you didn't want to get close to that beauty, right in this area.

01:35:57.800 --> 01:36:04.800
There was a bench down in here that you could probably have walked out on and seen a bottom,

01:36:04.800 --> 01:36:05.800
but you'd have fallen off.

01:36:05.800 --> 01:36:07.800
It would have spoiled your whole day.

01:36:07.800 --> 01:36:16.800
I'm sorry that you get the flight controllers mad because you didn't get back to the limb on

01:36:16.800 --> 01:36:17.800
time.

01:36:17.800 --> 01:36:18.800
Yeah.

